# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aleutian-islands-campaign
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The **10th Mountain Division (Light Infantry)** is a light infantry division in the United States Army based at Fort Drum, New York.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Formerly designated as a mountain warfare unit, the division was the only one of its size in the U.S. military to receive specialized training for fighting in mountainous conditions.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Originally activated as the **10th Light Division (Alpine)** in 1943, the division was redesignated the 10th Mountain Division in 1944 and fought in the mountains of Italy in some of the roughest terrain in World War II.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 5 May 1945, the division reached Nauders, Austria, just beyond the Reschen Pass, where it made contact with German s being pushed south by the U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] A status quo was maintained until the enemy headquarters involved had completed their surrender to the Seventh.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 6 May, 10th Mountain troops met the 44th Infantry Division of Seventh Army.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Following the war, the division was deactivated, only to be reactivated and redesignated as the **10th Infantry Division** in 1948.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division first acted as a training division and, in 1954, was converted to a full combat division and, in 1955, was sent to Germany before being deactivated again in 1958.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Reactivated again in 1985, the division was designated the 10th Mountain Division (Light Infantry) to historically tie it to the World War II division and to also better describe its modern disposition.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Since its reactivation, the division or elements of the division have deployed numerous times.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Since 2001, the 10th Mountain Division has been the most deployed unit in the entire US military.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Its combat brigades have seen over 30 deployments, to both Iraq and Afghanistan, in support of Operation Iraqi Freedom and Operation Enduring Freedom, as well as Syria and parts of Africa in support of Operation Inherent Resolve.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In November 1939, two months after World War II broke out in Europe, during the Soviet Union's invasion of Finland, Red Army efforts were frustrated following the destruction of two armored divisions by Finnish soldiers on skis.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The conflict caught attention as the outnumbered and outgunned Finnish soldiers were able to use the difficult local terrain to their advantage, severely hampering the Soviet attacks and embarrassing their military.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Upon seeing the effectiveness of these troops, Charles Minot "Minnie" Dole, the president of the National Ski Patrol, began to lobby the War Department of the need for a similar unit of troops in the United States Army, trained for fighting in winter and mountain warfare.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In September 1940, Dole was able to present his case to General George C.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Marshall, the Army Chief of Staff, who agreed with Dole's assessment, deciding to create a "Mountain" unit for fighting in harsh terrain.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Army authorized the formation of the platoon-sized Army Ski Patrol in November 1940.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The first Patrol was formed at Camp Murray as part of the 41st Infantry Division under Lt.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Phelps (later to become commanding General of the 41st).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The army, prompted by fears that its standing would not perform well in the event of a winter attack on the Northeastern coast, as well as knowledge that the German Army already had three mountain warfare divisions known as Gebirgsjäger, approved the concept for a division.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] This required an overhaul of U.S. military doctrine, as the concept of winter warfare had not been tested in the army since 1914.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] At first, planners envisioned ten mountain divisions, but personnel shortages revised the goal to three.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Eventually, the 10th Mountain Division would be the only one brought to active duty.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The Italian military had lost a disastrous 25,000 men in the campaign because of their lack of preparedness to fight in the mountains.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 22 October 1941, General Marshall decided to form the first battalion of mountain warfare troops for a new mountain division.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The Ski Patrol would assist in its training.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] It was the first mountain warfare unit in U.S. military history.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The National Ski Patrol took on the unique role of recruiting for the 87th Infantry Regiment and later the division, becoming the only civilian recruiting agency in military history.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Army planners favored recruiting experienced skiers for the unit instead of trying to train standing troops in mountain warfare, so Dole recruited from schools, universities, and ski clubs for the unit.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 87th trained in harsh conditions, including Mount Rainier's 14,411-foot (4,392 m) peak, throughout 1942 as more recruits were brought in to form the division.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Initial training was conducted by Olympian Rolf Monsen.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] A new garrison was built for the division in central Colorado at Camp Hale, at an elevation of 9,200 feet (2,800 m) above sea level.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The **10th Light Division (Alpine)** was constituted on 10 July 1943 and activated five days later at Camp Hale under the command of Brigadier General Lloyd E.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Culin Jr. assigned as his assistant division commander (ADC).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Light Division was centered on regimental commands; the 85th, 86th, and 87th Infantry Regiments.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division faced many difficulties in the new training, which had no established army doctrine.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Light Division was unique in that it was the only division in the army with three field artillery battalions instead of four.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] It was equipped with vehicles specialized in snow operation, such as the M29 Weasel, and winter weather gear, such as white camouflage and skis specifically designed for the division.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division practiced its rock climbing skills in preparation for the invasion of Italy on the challenging peaks of Seneca Rocks in West Virginia.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Its specialized training culminated with what were known as the "D-Series" ("D" for "Divisional"), military maneuvers on the divisional level in the Colorado Rockies in Winter conditions.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Beginning 26 March 1944, the exercises were intended to last five weeks.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The soldiers endured an adverse environment, and "tactical conditions" that banned open fires in sub-zero temperatures.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] As a result, the exercises were ended after 3 weeks.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Official statistics recorded 195 cases of frostbite and 340 other incapacitating injuries.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 22 June 1944, the division was shipped to Camp Swift, Texas, to prepare for maneuvers in Louisiana, which were later canceled.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] A period of acclimation to a low altitude and hot climate was thought necessary to prepare for this training.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 6 November 1944, the 10th Division was redesignated the **10th Mountain Division**.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] That same month, the blue and white "Mountain" tab was authorized for the division's new shoulder sleeve insignia.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Also in November, the division received a new commander, Brigadier General George Price Hays, a Medal of Honor recipient and a distinguished veteran of World War I.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On January 4, 1945, he received a promotion to major general.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division sailed for the Italian front in two parts, with the 86th Infantry and support leaving Camp Patrick Henry, Virginia on 11 December 1944 aboard the SS *Argentina* and arriving in Naples, Italy on 22 December.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 85th and 87th Infantry left Hampton Roads, Virginia on 4 January 1945 aboard the SS *West Point* and arrived on 13 January 1945.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] By 6 January, its support units were preparing to head to the front lines.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] It was attached to Major General Willis D.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Crittenberger's IV Corps, part of the American Fifth Army, commanded by Lieutenant General Lucian Truscott.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] By 8 January, the 86th Infantry had moved to Bagni di Lucca near Mount Belvedere in preparation for an offensive by the Fifth Army to capture the mountain along with surrounding high ground, which allowed the Axis to block advances to Po Valley.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Starting 14 January, the division began moving to Pisa as part of the Fifth Army massing for this attack.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] By 20 January, all three of the 10th's regiments were on or near the front line between the Serchio Valley and Mt.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Barlow commanded the 85th Regiment, Col.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] While the Brazilian division was in charge of taking Monte Castello and *Castelnuovo* di Vergato, the 10th Mountain Division was responsible for the Mount Belvedere area, climbing nearby Riva Ridge during the night of 18 February and attacking Mount della Torraccia on 20 February.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] These peaks were cleared after four days of heavy fighting, as Axis troops launched several counterattacks in these positions.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In early March, the division fought its way north of Canolle and moved to within 15 miles (24 km) of Bologna.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 5 March, while Brazilian units captured Castelnuovo, the 85th and the 87th Infantry took respectively Mount Della Spe and Castel D'Aiano, cutting the Axis routes of resupply and communication into the Po Valley, setting the stage for the next Fifth Army offensive.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division maintained defensive positions in this area for three weeks, anticipating a counteroffensive by the German s.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In the final days of April 1945, as German defenses in northern Italy collapsed, the 10th Mountain Division advanced north toward Lake Garda in pursuit of retreating s.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The difficult terrain and destroyed infrastructure around the lake required the use of amphibious DUKW vehicles for transport and assault.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On the night of 30 April, one such vehicle carrying 25 soldiers sank during the crossing, resulting in one of the last and most tragic losses of the Italian campaign.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] That same day, the division's newly appointed Assistant Commander, Colonel William Orlando Darby—founder of the U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Army Rangers—was killed by artillery fire in Torbole, together with Sergeant Major John T.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The events at Lake Garda marked the final combat actions for the 10th Mountain Division in Europe and have since become a lasting symbol of the cost of liberation.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Their story, long preserved by veterans and local historians, was later chronicled through research and documentary projects led by Italian and American collaborators, including Associazione Benàch and the 2023 film *The Lost Mountaineers*.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division resumed its attack on 14 April 1945, pressing forward on multiple axes.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] That day it assaulted Torre Iussi and Rocca Roffeno, north of Mount Della Spe.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] After stiff fighting, on 17 April it broke through the German Gothic Line defenses, opening the way into the Po Valley.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Over the next days the advance continued: on 20 April the 10th captured Mongiorgio and pushed into the Po plain, taking key positions at Pradalbino and Bomporto.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division crossed the Po River at San Benedetto Po on 23 April, reached Verona on 25 April, and encountered heavy resistance in the areas of Torbole and Nago.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Because the routes around Lake Garda had been rendered impassable by destroyed tunnels and bridges, the division carried out an amphibious crossing of the lake using DUKW vehicles.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 30 April it secured Gargnano and Porto di Tremosine on the western shore, effectively ending organized German resistance in northern Italy.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] That same night, however, a tragic accident occurred.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] During a night operation to transport troops and equipment across Lake Garda from Torbole toward the northern shore, one DUKW carrying 25 men of the 10th Mountain Division sank in deep water during rough weather.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The vehicle, heavily loaded with men, a 75 mm pack howitzer, ammunition, and gear, began taking on water and foundered before rescue could reach it.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Hough, survived; the others were declared Missing in Action (MIA) and remain unaccounted for.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The site of the sinking remained unknown for decades, despite repeated efforts by the U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Army, local divers, and underwater archaeology teams.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2012, after several unsuccessful surveys, the Italian volunteer rescue group Volontari del Garda located the wreck upright on the lakebed using sonar and remotely operated vehicles.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The ongoing research and commemorative work were later supported by the Italian historical association Associazione Benàch, which collaborated with local authorities and U.S. veterans’ families to preserve the memory of the missing soldiers.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 2023 documentary *The Lost Mountaineers*, produced by the Fondazione Museo Storico del Trentino in collaboration with Associazione Benàch, chronicles these final days of combat and the search for the lost soldiers.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The film reconstructs the events leading to the sinking, the experiences of the men aboard, and the decades-long recovery efforts.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] It also situates the tragedy within the wider story of the 10th Mountain Divisions campaign in northern Italy and its human cost.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On the same day, 30 April 1945, the division also suffered the loss of its Assistant Division Commander, Colonel William O.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] While in Torbole on the northern shore of Lake Garda, Darby was killed by an enemy artillery shell explosion along with his Sergeant Major, John T.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Darby had been appointed to the division only days earlier, following the wounding of Brigadier General Robinson E.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Duff, and was directing the final movements of the divisions advance when he was struck by shrapnel.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] His death came just hours before the announcement of the German surrender in Italy.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] After the German capitulation on 2 May 1945, the division shifted to security and occupation duties.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 5 May it reached Nauders, Austria, just beyond the Reschen Pass, where it linked up with elements of the U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Between 2 May and Victory in Europe Day (8 May), the 10th Mountain Division accepted the surrender of German units and secured key areas in northeastern Italy and western Slovenia.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] By 20 May it had redeployed to Udine, joining the British Eighth Army to prevent further westward movement of Yugoslav troops.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In July, the Department of War assigned the 10th Mountain to the Pacific theater; after a month's furlough the men would assemble at Camp Carson, where they would train for Operation Downfall, the invasion of mainland Japan.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Between 26 July and 2 August the three regiments boarded ships for the return voyage to the United States; the day before the first of these regiments, the 86th Mountain Infantry, disembarked at Hampton Roads, Hiroshima was leveled by an atom bomb.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Three days after the rest of the division landed stateside on 11 August, Japan officially surrendered.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division was demobilized and inactivated on 30 November 1945 at Camp Carson, Colorado.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] During World War II, the 10th Mountain Division suffered 992 killed in action and 4,154 wounded in action in 114 days of combat.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Soldiers of the division were awarded one Medal of Honor (John D.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Magrath), three Distinguished Service Crosses, one Distinguished Service Medal, 449 Silver Star Medals, seven Legion of Merit Medals, 15 Soldier's Medals, and 7,729 Bronze Star Medals.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division itself was awarded two campaign streamers.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In June 1948, the division was rebuilt and activated at Fort Riley, Kansas to serve as a training division.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Without its "Mountain" tab, the division served as the 10th Infantry Division for the next ten .
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The unit was charged with processing and training replacements in large numbers.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] This mission was expanded with the outbreak of the Korean War in 1950.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] By 1953, the division had trained 123,000 new Army recruits at Fort Riley.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 1954, the division was converted to a combat division once again, though it did not regain its "Mountain" status.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Using equipment from the deactivating 37th Infantry Division, the **10th Infantry Division** was deployed to Germany in 1955, replacing the 1st Infantry Division at Würzburg, serving as part of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) defensive .
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division served in Germany for four , until it was rotated out and replaced by the 3rd Infantry Division.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division moved to Fort Benning, Georgia, and was inactivated on 14 June 1958.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 13 February 1985, the 10th Mountain Division (Light Infantry) was reactivated at Fort Drum, New York.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In accordance with the Reorganization Objective Army Divisions plan, the division was no longer centered on regiments, instead two brigades were activated under the division.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 1st Brigade, 10th Mountain Division (commanded by then Colonel John M.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Keane, later 4-Star General and Army Vice Chief of Staff) and Division Artillery were activated at Fort Drum, while the 2nd Brigade, 10th Mountain Division was activated at Fort Benning, moving to Fort Drum in 1988.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division was also assigned a round-out brigade from the Army National Guard, the 27th Infantry Brigade.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division was specially designed as a light infantry division able to rapidly deploy.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In this process, it lost its mountain warfare capability, but its light infantry organization still made it versatile for difficult terrain.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Equipment design was oriented toward reduced size and weight for reasons of both strategic and tactical mobility.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division also received a distinctive unit insignia.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 1990, the division sent 1,200 soldiers to support Operation Desert Storm.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Two infantry platoons from the division were among those sent: 1st Platoon Bravo Company 1/22 and the 1/22 Scout Platoon.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Once in Iraq, the scouts were sent home and First Platoon was left as a counterintelligence .
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Performing three-man 24hr patrols through the remainder of their deployment, this platoon was widely regarded as the division's best at that time.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Following a cease-fire in March 1991, the support soldiers began redeploying to Fort Drum through June of that year.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Hurricane Andrew struck South Florida on 24 August 1992, killing 13 people, leaving another 250,000 homeless, and causing damages in excess of $20 billion.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 27 August 1992, the 10th Mountain Division assumed responsibility for Hurricane Andrew disaster relief as Task Mountain.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Division soldiers set up relief camps, distributed food, clothing, medical necessities, and building supplies, as well as helping to homes and clear debris.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The last of the 6,000 division soldiers deployed to Florida returned home in October 1992.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 3 December 1992, the division headquarters was designated as the headquarters for all Army s (ARFOR) of the Unified Task (UNITAF) for Operation Restore Hope.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Arnold, the division Commander, was named Army s commander.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division's mission was to secure major cities and roads to provide safe passage of relief supplies to the Somali population suffering from the effects of the Somali Civil War.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Due to 10th Mountain Division efforts, humanitarian agencies declared an end to the food emergency and factional fighting decreased.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] When Task Ranger and the SAR team were pinned down during a raid in what later became known as the Battle of Mogadishu, the 10th Mountain Division provided infantry for the UN quick reaction sent to rescue them.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division had two soldiers killed in the fighting, which was the longest sustained firefight by regular U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division began a gradual reduction of s in Somalia in February 1994, until the last soldiers of the 2nd Battalion, 22nd Infantry returned to the United States in March 1994.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division formed the nucleus of the Multinational Haiti (MNF Haiti) and Joint Task 190 (JTF 190) in Haiti during Operation Uphold Democracy.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] More than 8,600 of the division's troops deployed during this operation.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 19 September 1994, the 1st Brigade conducted the Army's first air assault from aircraft carrier USS *Dwight D.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] This consisted of 54 helicopters and almost 2,000 soldiers.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] They occupied the Port-au-Prince International Airport.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] This was the largest Army air operation conducted from a carrier since the Doolittle Raid in World War II.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division's mission was to create a secure and stable environment so the government of Haitian President Jean-Bertrand Aristide could be reestablished and democratic s held.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] After this was accomplished, the 10th Mountain Division handed over control of the MNF-Haiti to the 25th Infantry Division on 15 January 1995.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division redeployed the last of its soldiers who served in Haiti by 31 January 1995.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In the fall of 1998, the division received notice that it would be serving as senior headquarters of Task Eagle, providing a peacekeeping to support the ongoing operation within the Multi-National Division-North area of responsibility in Bosnia and Herzegovina.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Selected division units began deploying in late summer, approximately 3,000 division soldiers deployed.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] After performing their mission in Bosnia, the division units conducted a transfer of authority, relinquishing their assignments to soldiers of the 49th Armored Division, Texas National Guard.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] By early summer 2000, all 10th Mountain Division soldiers had returned safely to Fort Drum.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] During the 2000 presidential , the readiness of the 10th Mountain Division became a political issue when George W.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Bush asserted that the division was "not ready for duty." He attributed the division's low readiness to the frequent deployments throughout the 1990s without time in between for division elements to retrain and refit.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] General Accounting Office in July 2000 also noted that although the entire 10th Mountain Division was not deployed to the contingencies at once, "deployment of key components—especially headquarters—makes these divisions unavailable for deployment elsewhere in case of a major war".
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Conservative think tank The Heritage Foundation agreed with these sentiments, charging that the U.S. military overall was not prepared for war due to post–Cold War drawdowns of the U.S. military.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The Army responded that, though the 10th Mountain Division had been unprepared following its deployment as Task Eagle, that the unit was fully prepared for combat by late 2000 despite being undermanned.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Still, the Army moved the 10th Mountain Division down on the deployment list, allowing it time to retrain and refit.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2002, columnist and highly decorated military veteran David Hackworth again criticized the 10th Mountain Division for being unprepared due to lack of training, low physical fitness, unprepared leadership, and low morale.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] He said the division was no longer capable of mountain warfare.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] These concerns were quickly debunked as the 10th Mountain Division was the first conventional unit in the entire US military to be deployed to Afghanistan, seeing heavy combat.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Following the 11 September 2001 attacks, elements of the division, including its special troops battalion and 1st Battalion, 87th Infantry Regiment (1-87th) infantry deployed to Afghanistan as part of Operation Enduring Freedom in late 2001.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] This was the first conventional unit to be deployed in the entire US military.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division headquarters arrived at Karshi-Khanabad Air Base, under Major General Franklin L.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Hagenbeck, on 12 December 2001 to function as the Combined s Land Component Command (CFLCC) (Forward).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] This command served as the representative for Lieutenant General Paul T.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Army/CFLCC commanding general (CG) in the theater of operations.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division was also intended to defend Uzbekistan against attacks by the Islamic Movement of Uzbekistan, which was seeking to overthrow Islam Karimov's secular government.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 13 February 2002, Mikolashek ordered Hagenbeck to move CFLCC (Forward) to Bagram airfield located at Bagram and 2 days later the headquarters was officially redesignated as Combined Joint Task (CJTF) Mountain.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] It assumed responsibility for the planning and execution of what had then become known as Operation Anaconda.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Elements of the division, primarily 1-87th Infantry, remained in the country until mid-2002, fighting to secure remote areas of the country and participating in prominent operations such as Operation Anaconda, the Fall of Mazar-i-Sharif, and the Battle of Qala-i-Jangi.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] These 1-87th Infantry soldiers became the first U.S. conventional s to fight in Afghanistan.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division also participated in fighting in the Shahi Khot Valley in 2002.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In June 2002, elements of the 82nd Airborne Division arrived to relieve CJTF Mountain, and in September, Major General John R.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Vines and his Combined Task 82 relieved CJTF Mountain as the major subordinate headquarters to Combined Joint Task 180.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Upon the return of the battalions, they were welcomed home and praised by President Bush.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2003, the division's headquarters, along with the 1st Brigade, returned to Afghanistan.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] During that time, they operated in the frontier regions of the country such as Paktika Province, going to places previously untouched by the war in search of Taliban and Al-Qaeda s.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Fighting in several small-scale conflicts such as Operation Avalanche, Operation Mountain Resolve, and Operation Mountain Viper, the division maintained a strategy of small units moving through remote regions of the country to interact directly with the population and drive out insurgents.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 1st Brigade also undertook a number of humanitarian missions.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2003 and into 2004, the division's aviation brigade deployed for the first time to Afghanistan.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] As the only aviation brigade in the theater, the brigade provided air support for all U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade's mission at that time focused on close air support, medevac missions, and other duties involving combat with Taliban and Al-Qaeda s in the country.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division was the first unit to introduce contract working dogs into southern Afghanistan.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In the spring of 2004, they had Patriot K-9 Services supply 20 dog teams based at KAF.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The teams were trained to detect explosives and perform patrol duties throughout the region.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade returned to Fort Drum in 2004.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On the return of the division headquarters and 1st Brigade, the 10th Mountain Division began the process of transformation into a modular division.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 16 September 2004, the division headquarters finished its transformation, adding the 10th Mountain Division Special Troops Battalion.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 1st Brigade became the 1st Brigade Combat Team, while the 3rd Brigade Combat Team, 10th Mountain Division was activated for the first time.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In January 2005, the 4th Brigade Combat Team, 10th Mountain Division was activated at Fort Polk, Louisiana.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] 2nd Brigade Combat Team would not be transformed until September 2005, pending a deployment to Iraq.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In late 2004, the 2nd Brigade Combat Team was deployed to Iraq supporting Operation Iraqi Freedom.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 2nd Brigade Combat Team undertook combat operations in western Baghdad, an area of responsibility that included Abu Ghraib, Mansour, and Route Irish.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Around that time, the 1st Brigade Combat Team deployed back to Iraq, staying in the country until 2006.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The next time the 1st Brigade Combat Team was deployed was during the Surge for 15 months in Iraq.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Northern Iraq was the theater of operations for 1 BCT from August 2007 until November 2008.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 4th BCT operated in Northeast Baghdad under the 4th Infantry Division headquarters from November 2007 until January 2009.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain participated in larger-scale operations, such as Operation Phantom Phoenix.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] After a one-year rest, the headquarters of the 10th Mountain Division was deployed to Iraq for the first time in April 2008.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division headquarters transferred authority for MND-S to the 34th Infantry Division, Minnesota Army National Guard on 20 May 2009.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 2nd Brigade Combat Team was scheduled to deploy to Iraq in the fall of 2009, as a part of the 2009–2010 rotation to Iraq.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division headquarters, the 3rd Brigade Combat Team, and two Battalion Task s from the 4th Brigade Combat Team deployed to Afghanistan in 2005, staying in the country until 2006.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division and brigade served in the eastern region of the country, along the border with Pakistan, fulfilling a similar role as it did during its previous deployment.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] During this time, the deployment of the brigade was extended along with that of the 4th Brigade, 82nd Airborne Division.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] It was eventually replaced by the 173rd Airborne Brigade Combat Team which was rerouted from Iraq.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In the winter of 2006, the 10th Aviation Brigade, 10th Mountain Division, was deployed again to Afghanistan to support Operation Enduring Freedom as the only aviation brigade in the theater, stationed at Bagram Air Base, Afghanistan.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Named "Task Falcon," the brigade's mission was to conduct aviation operations to destroy insurgents and anti-coalition militia in an effort to help build the Afghan National Security 's capability and allow the Afghan government to increase its capabilities.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In addition, the Task provided logistical and combat support for International Security Assistance s throughout the country.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 3rd Brigade Combat Team was slated to deploy to Iraq in 2009, but that deployment was rerouted.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In January 2009, the 3rd BCT instead deployed to Kunar, Logar and Wardak Provinces, eastern Afghanistan to relieve the 101st Airborne Division, as part of a new buildup of US s in that country.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade was responsible for expanding forward operating bases and combat outposts (COPs) in the region, as well as strengthening US military presence in preparation for additional US s to arrive.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 1st Brigade Combat Team was scheduled to deploy to Iraq in late 2009 but deployed instead to Afghanistan in March 2010 for 13 months.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] 1-87th Infantry deployed to Kunduz and Baghlan Provinces, establishing remote combat outposts (COPs) against the Taliban after they had taken control of these provinces over the last several .
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Notably, Blacksheep Company was responsible for numerous large-scale engagements, including the Battle of Shahabuddin and securing a High-Value Target (HVT) after an air assault raid.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] This deployment was transformational to the Counterinsurgency in Northern Afghanistan campaign of the war.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The Brigade again deployed to Afghanistan in late 2012 to Ghazni Provence for nine months.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 3rd Brigade Combat Team deployed to Kandahar Province, southern Afghanistan in March 2011, again relieving the 101st Airborne Division.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] During this deployment, 3rd BCT mainly occupied forward operating bases (FOBs) and combat outposts (COPs) in the Maywand, Zhari, and Arghandab Districts of Kandahar Province.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade was redeployed to Fort Drum in March 2012 after a twelve-month deployment.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 4th Brigade Combat Team deployed to Regional Command East, under the 101st Airborne Division from October 2010 until their redeployment in October 2011.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 4th BCT deployed to both Wardak and Logar provinces.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] During this deployment, they went to places such as Chakh Valley in Wardak Province and Charkh Valley in Logar Province in search of elements of the Haqqani Network.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In May 2013, the brigade deployed again to Afghanistan returning home in February 2014.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 5 December 2019, the Department of the Army announced that the 1st Brigade Combat Team would replace the 3rd Brigade Combat Team, 82nd Airborne Division as part of a unit rotation in support of Operation Freedom's Sentinel.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade deployed to Afghanistan in February 2020.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] On 3 November 2016, *Stars and Stripes* reported that the 10th Combat Aviation Brigade would deploy 1,750 soldiers to Eastern Europe in March 2017, in support of Operation Atlantic Resolve – as part of NATO efforts to reassure Eastern Europe in response to Russian intervention in Ukraine in 2014.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade arrived with approximately 60 aircraft, including CH-47 Chinooks, UH-60 Blackhawks, and medevac helicopters.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The brigade was headquartered in Germany and the brigade's units were forward-based at locations in Latvia, Romania, and Poland.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Between late summer and early fall 2015, as well as again in 2016, 1,250 soldiers from the 1st Brigade Combat Team were deployed to Iraq to support Operation Inherent Resolve.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] During the two deployments the brigade spent in Iraq, they fought to regain control of the cities of Ramadi, Fallujah, and Mosul from the Islamic State of Iraq and Syria.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2022 the unit would redeploy again, in support of Operation Inherent Resolve.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division was awarded two campaign streamers in World War II, one campaign streamer for Somalia, and four campaign streamers in the war on terrorism, for a total of seven campaign streamers and three unit decorations in its operational history.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Note that some of the division's brigades received more or fewer decorations depending on their individual deployments.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] In 2026, the Army announced that it has officially approved the formerly unauthorized ski trooper insignia to be worn on the AGSU garrison cap for soldiers in the 10th Mountain Division.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Skiing associations subsequently contend that veterans of the 10th Mountain Division had a substantial effect on the post–World War II development of skiing as a vacation industry and major sport.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Ex-soldiers from the 10th laid out ski hills, designed ski lifts, became ski coaches, racers, instructors, patrollers, shop owners, and filmmakers.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] They wrote and published ski magazines, opened ski schools, improved ski equipment, and developed ski resorts.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Up to 2,000 of the division's troops were involved in skiing-related professions after the war, and at least 60 ski resorts were founded by men of the division.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] People associated with the 10th Mountain Division later went on to achieve notability in other fields.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Bill Bowerman, former executive director and Sierra Club leader David R.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Brower, former United States Ski Team member World War II civilian mountaineer trainer H.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Additionally, five members of the division have been awarded the Medal of Honor.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Magrath became the first member of the division to receive this award (posthumously) during World War II.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Monti, received it posthumously in 2009, for actions during a combat operation on 21 June 2006 in Afghanistan.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Swenson, received it in 2013, for actions on 8 September 2009, during the Battle of Ganjgal in Afghanistan.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] Atkins, received it posthumously on 27 March 2019, for actions on 1 June 2007 during a patrol in Iraq.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The fifth, Michael Ollis, received it posthumously on 2 March 2026, for actions on 28 August 2013 during an attack in Afghanistan.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The division's efforts in Afghanistan during Operation Enduring Freedom and beyond led to the division being referred to as the "Tribe of Crossed Swords" by some Afghans.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division's first appearance in popular literature was the semi-fictional novel by Frank Harper, *Night Climb*, published in 1946 by Longsman, Green, and Company.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The title of this book came from the unit's celebrated night ascent of Riva Ridge as part of the Battle of Mount Belvedere, and the novel follows the actions of several members through Operation Encore and Operation Craftsman to the end of hostilities in Italy.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The Division was later the subject of the 1996 film *Fire on the Mountain*, which documented its exploits during World War II.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] The 10th Mountain Division is also a prominent element of the book *Black Hawk Down* and film *by the same name*, which portrays the Battle of Mogadishu and the division's participation in that conflict.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p01] John, referencing his time spent with the 10th Mountain Division in Afghanistan.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/10th-mountain-division-p02] This division consists of a division headquarters and headquarters battalion, three infantry brigade combat teams, a division artillery, a combat aviation brigade, and a division sustainment brigade.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] The **18th Fighter Interceptor Squadron** (18th FIS) is a subordinate unit of the 354th Fighter Wing based at Eielson Air Force Base in Alaska, and flies the Block 30 General Dynamics F-16C/D aircraft.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] The **18th Fighter Interceptor Squadron** provides aerospace control for homeland defense missions in the Alaska Theater of Operations.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] Activated in 1940 as a Southwest Air District pursuit squadron, equipped with a variety of 1930s-era pursuit aircraft.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] Re-equipped with P-38 Lightning fighters and deployed to Alaska, engaged in combat during the Aleutian Campaign, 1942–1943.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] Remained in Alaska as part of the air defense forces until inactivated in August 1946.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] Reactivated in 1952 as part of Air Defense Command as an air defense squadron, initially equipped with F-86A Sabre day fighters, initially being assigned to Minneapolis Airport, Minnesota with a mission for the air defense of the Upper Great Lakes region.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] Re-equipped in 1954 with F-89D Scorpions and moved to Ladd AFB, Alaska for interceptor duty in the Fairbanks area as part of Alaskan Air Command.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] Returned to the CONUS in 1957 and upgraded to F-102 Delta Dagger interceptors at the new Wurtsmith Air Force Base, Michigan.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] Reassigned to Grand Forks AFB, North Dakota in 1960 and received the new McDonnell F-101B Voodoo supersonic interceptor, and the F-101F operational and conversion trainer.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] The two-seat trainer version was equipped with dual controls, but carried the same armament as the F-101B and were fully combat-capable.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] Inactivated in April 1971 as part of the drawdown of ADC interceptor bases, the aircraft being passed along to the Air National Guard.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] On 1 October 1977 the squadron was reactivated under the 343rd Tactical Fighter Group, assigned to the 21st Composite Wing of Alaskan Air Command flying the McDonnell Douglas F-4E Phantom II at Elmendorf AFB, Alaska.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] The squadron specialized in air-to-ground operations within the 21st Composite Wing.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] The squadron moved to Eielson AFB, Alaska at the end of 1981 and began converting to the Fairchild Republic A-10A Thunderbolt II.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] From 1981 to 1991 the squadron conducted air-to-ground operations with the A-10, assigned to the 343rd Tactical Fighter Wing before converting to the Lockheed Martin F-16 Fighting Falcon.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] In 1991, the squadron converted to the Lockheed Martin F-16 Fighting Falcon.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] In 1997, elements of the 18th FS deployed to Singapore and Malaysia to take part in dissimilar air combat tactic training as part of Exercises Commando Sling and Cope Taufan, respectively.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] The Cope Taufan deployment marked the first time Pacific Air Forces' F-16s had flown against MiG-29s.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] The unit deployed to Ahmad al-Jaber Air Base, Kuwait, October–December 1998 to support Operation Southern Watch.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] Later, the squadron deployed to Incirlik Air Base, Turkey, September–December 2000, in support of Operation Northern Watch.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] For this deployment, the squadron employed 5 F-16 aircraft and 110 personnel, conducting the first ever Combat Search and Rescue support tasking for an F-16 squadron.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] After the 11 September 2001 attacks, the 18th FS was called to provide eight aircraft for Alaska NORAD air defense during Operation NOBLE EAGLE, though the aircraft were not launched.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] The squadron's next deployment was to Ahmed Al Jaber Air Base from December 2001 to March 2002 to support simultaneous combat operations for Operations Southern Watch and Operation Enduring Freedom.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] They flew more than 3,200 hours in only 3 months, an amazing feat for the 142 Blue Foxes who deployed with only 10 aircraft.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] During that time, the 18th FS flew missions in support of Operation Anaconda, including one in the Shah-i-Kot Valley on 2 March when U.S. forces, engaged in a firefight with Taliban and Al Qaeda forces, called for aerial assistance.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] A number of Blue Foxes responded, dropping bombs with pinpoint accuracy on the opposing forces.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] Burt Bartley, the 18 FS commander at the time, received the Silver Star for strafing and dropping 500 lbs Laser-guided bombs on what would later be known as "The Battle for Roberts Ridge".
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] The squadron deployed to Andersen Air Force Base, Guam in support of Operation Noble Eagle during March 2003.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] The unit also participated in Exercise Commando Sling in October 2003.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] As part of the change from COPE THUNDER to Red Flag-Alaska, the 18th FS was re-designated the 18th Aggressor Squadron.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] The squadron trains in the same manner as the aggressors at Nellis Air Force Base, learning the flying styles and abilities of foreign air forces in order to train USAF pilots against realistic opposition.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] Aircraft changes entail sending all 18 of its Block 40 F-16 Fighting Falcons to Kunsan Air Base, Korea, and receiving 18 Block 30 F-16s from Kunsan.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] In 2013, the Air Force, responding to the Department of Defense strategy guidance of December 2012, proposed consolidating all fighter units in Alaska at Joint Base Elmendorf-Richardson.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] This would involve the move of the 18th from Eielson Air Force Base to Elmendorf.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] While the move was pending, in response to the sequestration of defense funds, the squadron's aircraft were grounded in the middle of April for a period of three months.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] The squadron move was strongly opposed by civic leaders from both Fairbanks and Anchorage, Alaska.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] The civic leaders were joined by the Alaska congressional delegation, who wrote language barring the use of funds in the Defense Appropriations Bill to move the squadron, and delayed the promotion of a lieutenant general until the Air Force addressed their questions concerning the move.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/18th-aggressor-squadron] The widespread opposition in Alaska to the squadron's move caused the Department of Defense to withdraw its recommendation and leave the squadron at Eielson.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Both the mushers and their dogs were portrayed as heroes in the newly popular medium of radio and received headline coverage in newspapers across the United States.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Balto, the lead sled dog on the final stretch into Nome, became the most famous canine celebrity of the era after Rin Tin Tin, and his statue is a popular tourist attraction in both New York City's Central Park and downtown Anchorage, Alaska.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Togo's team covered much of the most dangerous parts of the route and ran the farthest: Togo's team covered 261 miles (420 km) while Balto's team ran 55 miles (89 km).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] From November to July, the port on the southern shore of the Seward Peninsula of the Bering Sea was icebound and inaccessible by steamship.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The only link to the rest of the world during the winter was the Iditarod Trail, which ran 938 miles (1,510 km) from the port of Seward in the south, across several mountain ranges and the vast Alaska Interior, to the town of Nome.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In Alaska and other subarctic regions, the primary source of mail and needed supplies in 1925 was the dog sled.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Within a decade, bush flying became the dominant method of transportation during the winter months.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In the winter of 1924–1925, Curtis Welch was the only doctor in Nome.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He and four nurses, working at the small Maynard Columbus Hospital, served the town and the surrounding area.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After discovering the hospital's entire batch of diphtheria antitoxin had expired, Welch placed an order for more.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] However, the replacement shipment did not arrive before the port was closed by ice for the winter, and more could not be shipped in to Nome until spring.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In the next few weeks, after the number of cases grew and four children were dead—whom Welch had not been able to autopsy—he became increasingly concerned about diphtheria.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] By mid-January 1925, Welch officially diagnosed the first case of diphtheria in a three-year-old boy who died only two weeks after first becoming ill.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The following day, when a seven-year-old girl presented the same symptoms of diphtheria, Welch attempted to administer some of the expired antitoxin to see if it might still have any effect, but the girl died a few hours later.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Realizing that an epidemic was imminent, Welch called Nome's mayor, George Maynard, that same evening to arrange an emergency town council meeting.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The council immediately implemented a quarantine.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The following day, on January 22, 1925, Welch sent radio telegrams to all other major towns in Alaska alerting them of the public health risk.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He also requested assistance from the U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Despite the quarantine, there were over 20 confirmed cases of diphtheria and at least 50 more at risk by the end of January.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Without antitoxin, it was expected that in the surrounding region's population of around 10,000 people, the mortality rate could be close to 100 percent.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] A previous influenza pandemic had hit the area in 1918, causing fatalities in about 50 percent of the native population of Nome and 8% of the native population of Alaska.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] More than 1,000 people died in northwest Alaska, and approximately 2,000 across the state.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The majority were Alaska Natives who did not have any resistance to either disease.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] At the January 24 meeting of the board of health, superintendent Mark Summers of the Hammon Consolidated Gold Fields proposed a dogsled relay using two fast teams.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] One would start at Nenana, Alaska, the closest railhead on the Alaska Railroad, and the other at Nome, and they would meet roughly halfway in the town of Nulato.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The trip from Nulato to Nome normally took 30 days.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Curtis Welch estimated that the serum would last only six days under the brutal conditions of the trail.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Summers's employee, the Norwegian sled dog trainer and musher Leonhard Seppala, was chosen for the 630-mile (1,014 km) round trip from Nome to Nulato and back.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He had previously made the run in a record-breaking four days, won the All-Alaska Sweepstakes three times, and had become famous for his athletic ability and rapport with his Siberian huskies.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] His lead dog, the 12-year-old Togo, was equally famous for his leadership, intelligence, and ability to sense danger.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Maynard proposed flying the antitoxin by plane.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In 1925, planes were a relatively new technology, and Alaska's harsh winter weather made them unreliable.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Several test flights had been conducted the previous year between Fairbanks and McGrath, Alaska, to determine how well a reliable aircraft could handle the winter conditions.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The longest test flight flew a distance of only 260 miles (420 km), a little under half the necessary distance between Nenana and Nome.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The only planes operating in Alaska in 1925 were three vintage biplanes, which had been dismantled for the winter.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Their open cockpits and water-cooled engines would make these planes unfit for the trip as well.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Although it was potentially quicker, the proposal to deliver the antitoxin by flight was rejected by the board of health.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Instead, they voted unanimously for the dogsled relay.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala was notified that evening and immediately began preparations for the trip.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Public Health Service had located 1.1 million units of serum in West Coast hospitals which could be shipped to Seattle, Washington, and then transported to Alaska.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The next ship north would not arrive in Seattle until January 31, and it would take another six to seven days to arrive in Seward.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On January 26, 300,000 forgotten units of the antitoxin were located in a hospital in Anchorage.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The supply was wrapped in glass vials, then padded quilts, and finally a metallic cylinder weighing a little over 20 pounds (9 kg).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] At Governor Scott Bone's order, it was immediately shipped to Nenana and arrived the next day.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] While not sufficient to defeat the epidemic, the 300,000 units could slow the spread of the disease until the larger shipment arrived.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The mail route from Nenana to Nome spanned 674 miles (1,085 km) in total.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] It crossed the barren Alaska Interior, following the Tanana River for 137 miles (220 km) to the village Tanana at the junction with the Yukon River, and then following the Yukon for 230 miles (370 km) to Kaltag.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The route then passed west 90 miles (140 km) over the Kaltag Portage to Unalakleet on the shore of Norton Sound.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The route then continued for 208 miles (335 km) northwest around the southern shore of the Seward Peninsula with no protection from gales and blizzards, including a 42-mile (68 km) stretch across the shifting ice of the Bering Sea.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Edward Wetzler, the US Postal Service inspector for Nenana, contacted Tom Parson, an agent of the Northern Commercial Company, contracted to deliver mail between Fairbanks and Unalakleet.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Telephones and telegraphs turned the drivers back to their assigned roadhouses.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The mail carriers held a revered position in the territory, and were the best dog mushers in Alaska.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The majority of relay drivers across the Interior were native Athabaskans, direct descendants of the original dog mushers.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The first musher in the relay was "Wild Bill" Shannon, who was handed the 20 pounds (9 kg) package at the train station in Nenana on January 27 at 9:00 pm AKST by night.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Despite a temperature of −50 °F (−46 °C), Shannon left immediately with his team of 9 inexperienced dogs, led by Blackie.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature began to drop, and the team was forced onto the colder ice of the river because the trail had been destroyed by horses.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Despite jogging alongside the sled to keep warm, Shannon developed hypothermia.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He reached Minto at 3 am, with parts of his face black from frostbite.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After warming the serum by the fire and resting for four hours, Shannon dropped three dogs and left with the remaining 8.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The three dogs died shortly after Shannon returned for them, and a fourth may have died as well.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Half-Athabaskan Edgar Kalland arrived in Minto the night before, and was sent back to Tolovana, traveling 70 mi (110 km) the day before the relay.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Shannon and his team arrived in bad condition at 11 am, and handed over the serum.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After warming the serum in the roadhouse, Kalland headed into the forest.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature had fallen to −56 °F (−49 °C), causing Kalland's hands to freeze to the sled's handlebar, requiring the owner of the Manley Hot Springs roadhouse to pour boiling water on the birch wood bar for thawing.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] No new cases of diphtheria were diagnosed on January 28, but two new cases were diagnosed on January 29.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The quarantine had been obeyed, but lack of diagnostic tools and the contagiousness of the strain rendered it ineffective.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] More units of serum were discovered around Juneau the same day.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] While no count exists, the estimate based on weight is roughly 125,000 units, enough to treat 4 to 6 patients.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The crisis had become headline news in newspapers, including in San Francisco, Cleveland, Washington D.C., and New York, and spread to the radio sets which were just becoming common.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The storm system from Alaska hit the contiguous United States, bringing record lows to New York, and freezing the Hudson River.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Maynard and Alaskan House Delegate Daniel Sutherland renewed their campaign for flying the remaining serum by plane.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Different proposals included flying a large aircraft 2,000 miles (3,200 km) from Seattle to Nome, carrying a plane to the edge of the pack ice via Navy ship and launching it, and the original plan of flying the serum from Fairbanks.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Despite receiving headline coverage across the country and support from Arctic explorer Roald Amundsen, the plans were rejected by experienced pilots, the Navy, and Governor Bone.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] As publisher and editor of the *Fairbanks Daily News-Miner* newspaper, William Fentress Thompson harshly criticized government officials for inaction and funded a private fleet of planes.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In response, Governor Bone decided to speed up the relay, authorizing additional drivers for Seppala's leg of the relay, so they could travel without rest.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala was still scheduled to cover the most dangerous leg, the shortcut across Norton Sound, but the telephone and telegraph systems bypassed the small villages he was passing through, and there was no way to tell him to wait at Shaktoolik.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The plan relied on the driver from the north catching Seppala on the trail.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Summers arranged for drivers along the last leg, including Seppala's colleague Gunnar Kaasen.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] From Manley Hot Springs, the serum passed through largely Athabascan hands before George Nollner delivered it to Charlie Evans at Bishop Mountain on January 30 at 3 am.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature had warmed slightly, but at −62 °F (−52 °C), was dropping again.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Evans relied on his lead dogs when he passed through ice fog where the Koyukuk River, flowing into the Yukon, had broken through and surged over the ice, but forgot to protect the groins of his two short-haired mixed breed lead dogs with rabbit skins.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Both dogs collapsed with frostbite, with Evans having to take their place himself pulling the sled.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He arrived at 10 am; both dogs were dead.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Tommy Patsy departed within half an hour.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The transport of the serum then parted ways with the Yukon River as the river turned south and the trail crossed the Kaltag Portage west to the coast.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Gonangnan saw the signs of a storm brewing, and decided not to take the shortcut across the dangerous ice of the Sound.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala was not there, but Henry Ivanoff was waiting just in case.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On January 30, the number of cases in Nome had reached 27 and the antitoxin was depleted.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] According to a reporter living in Nome, "All hope is in the dogs and their heroic drivers ...
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Nome appears to be a deserted city." With the report of Gonangnan's progress on January 31, Welch believed the serum would arrive there in February.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Leonhard Seppala and his dog sled team, with his lead dog Togo, travelled 91 miles (146 km) from Nome from January 27 to January 31 into the oncoming storm.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] They took the shortcut across the Norton Sound, and headed toward Shaktoolik.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature in Nome was a relatively warm −20 °F (−29 °C), but in Shaktoolik, the temperature was estimated at −30 °F (−34 °C), and the gale force winds causing a wind chill of −85 °F (−65 °C).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Henry Ivanoff's team ran into a reindeer and got tangled up just outside Shaktoolik.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala still believed he had more than 100 mi (160 km) to the original relay point in Nulato to go and had raced to get off the Norton Sound before the storm hit.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He was passing the team when Ivanoff shouted, "The serum!
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala turned around with the serum but it was dark by the time he got to Ungalik.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] But with the news of the worsening epidemic Ivanoff had shared, he decided not to stop and once again set out to brave the storm across the 20 miles (32 km) of exposed open ice of the Norton Sound.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature was estimated at −30 °F (−34 °C), but the wind chill with the gale force winds was −85 °F (−65 °C).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Togo led the team in a straight line through the dark, and they arrived at the roadhouse in Isaac's Point on the other side at 8 pm.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In one day, they had travelled 84 mi (135 km), averaging 8 mph (13 km/h).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The team rested, and departed at 2 am into the full power of the storm.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] During the night, the temperature dropped to −40 °F (−40 °C), and the wind increased to storm force (at least 65 mph [105 km/h]).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] While they slept, it had blown out to sea all the ice Seppala had just crossed.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] There was still some ice close to shore for the next part of their journey along the coast, but it was rough and starting to break up too.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] They stuck close to shore, and Togo picked his way carefully until they were back on solid ground.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Next they had to cross Little McKinley Mountain (1,200 feet [370 m]), another of the toughest parts of the trail because of the many up-and-down ridges.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The total elevation climbed in that section of over 8 miles (13 km) is 5,000 feet (1,500 m).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After descending to the next roadhouse in Golovin, Seppala passed the serum to Charlie Olsen on February 1 at 3 pm.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On February 1, the number of cases in Nome rose to 28.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The serum en route was sufficient to treat 30 people.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] With the powerful blizzard raging and winds of 80 mph (130 km/h), Welch ordered a stop to the relay until the storm passed, reasoning that a delay was better than the risk of losing all the serum.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Messages were left at Solomon and Point Safety before the lines went dead.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Olsen was blown off the trail, and suffered severe frostbite in his hands while putting blankets on his dogs.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He arrived at Bluff on February 1 at 7 pm in poor condition.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Gunnar Kaasen waited until 10 pm for the storm to break, but it only got worse and the drifts would soon block the trail, so he departed into a headwind.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Kaasen traveled through the night, through drifts, and river overflow over the 600-foot (183 m) Topkok Mountain.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Balto led the team through visibility so poor that Kaasen could not always see the dogs harnessed closest to the sled.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He was two miles (3 km) past Solomon before he realized it, and kept going.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The winds after Solomon were so severe that his sled flipped over and he almost lost the cylinder containing the serum when it fell off and became buried in the snow.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He also suffered frostbite when he had to use his bare hands to feel for the cylinder.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Kaasen reached Point Safety ahead of schedule on February 2, at 3 am.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Ed Rohn believed that Kaasen and the relay had halted at Solomon, so he was sleeping.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Since the weather was improving, it would take time to prepare Rohn's team, and Balto and the other dogs were moving well, Kaasen pressed on with the remaining 25 miles (40 km) to Nome, reaching Front Street at 5:30 am.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Not a single ampule was broken, and the antitoxin was thawed and ready by noon.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Together, the teams covered the 674 miles (1,085 km) in 1271⁄2 hours, which was considered a world record, done in extreme subzero temperatures in near-blizzard conditions and hurricane-force winds.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Margaret Curran from the Solomon Roadhouse was infected, which raised fears that the disease might spread from patrons of the roadhouse to other communities.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The 1.1 million units had left Seattle on January 31, and were not due by dog sled until February 8.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Welch asked for half the serum to be delivered by aircraft from Fairbanks.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He contacted Thompson and Sutherland, and Darling made a test flight the next morning.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] With his health advisor, Governor Bone concluded the cases in Nome were actually going down, and withheld permission, but preparations went ahead.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Navy moved a minesweeper north from Seattle, and the Signal Corps were ordered to light fires to guide the planes.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] By February 3, the original 300,000 units had proved to be still effective, and the epidemic was under control.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] A sixth death, probably unrelated to diphtheria, was widely reported as a new outbreak of the disease.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The batch from Seattle arrived on board the *Admiral Watson* on February 7.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Acceding to pressure, Governor Bone authorized half to be delivered by plane.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On February 8, the first half of the second shipment began its trip by dog sled, while the plane failed to start when a broken radiator shutter caused the engine to overheat.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The plane failed the next day as well, and the mission was scrapped.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Thompson was gracious in his editorials.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The second relay included many of the same drivers, and also faced harsh conditions.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Ed Rohn delivered the serum to Nome during another blizzard after a 90 miles (140 km) run on February 15.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The death toll from diphtheria in Nome is officially listed as either 5, 6, or 7, but Welch later estimated there were probably at least 100 additional cases among "the Eskimo camps outside the city.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The Natives have a habit of burying their children without reporting the death." Forty-three new cases were diagnosed in 1926, but they were easily managed with the fresh supply of serum.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] All participants in the dogsleds received letters of commendation from President Calvin Coolidge, and the Senate stopped work to recognize the event.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Each musher during the first relay received a gold medal from the H.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The mayor of Los Angeles presented a bone-shaped key to the city to Balto in front of City Hall and silent-film actress Mary Pickford put a wreath around the canine's neck.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Poems and letters from children poured in, and spontaneous fundraising campaigns sprang up around the country.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Gunnar Kaasen and his team became celebrities and toured the West Coast from February 1925 to February 1926, and also starred in a 30-minute film entitled *Balto's Race to Nome*.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] A statue of Balto by sculptor Frederick Roth was unveiled in New York City's Central Park during a visit on December 15, 1925.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Balto and the other dogs later became part of a sideshow and lived in horrible conditions until they were rescued by George Kimble, who organized a fundraising campaign by the children of Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On March 19, 1927, the dogs received a hero's welcome as they arrived at their permanent home at the Cleveland Zoo.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Because of his age, Balto was euthanized on March 14, 1933, at the age of 14.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He was mounted and placed on display in the Cleveland Museum of Natural History.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In October 1926, Seppala took Togo and his team on a tour from Seattle to California, and then across the Midwest to New England, and consistently drew huge crowds.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] They were featured at Madison Square Garden in New York City for 10 days, and Togo received a gold medal from Roald Amundsen.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In New England, Seppala's team of Siberians ran in many races, easily defeating the local Chinooks of Arthur Walden.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala entered into a partnership with Elizabeth M.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Ricker in Poland Spring, Maine, where many of his dogs went to live in retirement and contribute to their breeding program of Siberian sled dogs, including Togo, who sired many litters.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala visited Togo, and was by his side when he was euthanized on December 5, 1929, at the age of 16.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After his death, Seppala had Togo preserved and mounted, and today the dog is on display in a glass case at the Iditarod museum in Wasilla, Alaska.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Togo's prowess as a sled dog also led to his strengths being preserved through breeding, with his descendants contributing to the "Seppala Siberian Sleddog", a sought after working sled dog line, as well as the mainstream show-stock Siberian Husky gene pool.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] None of the other mushers received the same degree of attention, though Wild Bill Shannon briefly toured with Blackie.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The media largely ignored the Alaska Native mushers, who covered two-thirds of the distance to Nome.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The serum race helped spur the Air Mail Act of 1925, which was signed into law on February 2.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The bill allowed private aviation companies to bid on mail delivery contracts.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Technology improved and, within a decade, air mail routes were established in Alaska.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The last mail delivery by private dog sled under contract took place in 1938, and the last U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Post Office dog sled route closed in 1963.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Dog sledding remained popular in the rural interior but became nearly extinct when snowmobiles spread in the 1960s.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Mushing was revitalized as a recreational sport in the 1970s with the immense popularity of the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] While the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race, which runs more than 1,000 miles (1,600 km) from Anchorage to Nome, is based on the All-Alaska Sweepstakes, it has many traditions that commemorate the race to deliver the serum to Nome, especially Seppala and Togo.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The honorary musher for the first seven races was Leonhard Seppala.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Other serum run participants, including "Wild Bill" Shannon, Edgar Kalland, Bill McCarty, Charlie Evans, Edgar Nollner, Harry Pitka, and Henry Ivanoff have also been honored.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The 2005 Iditarod honored Jirdes Winther Baxter, the last known survivor of the epidemic.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The position is now known as Leonhard Seppala's Honorary Musher, the Leonhard Seppala Humanitarian Award is given to the musher who provides the best dog care while remaining competitive, and the Leonhard Seppala Heritage Grant is an Iditarod scholarship.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The two races follow the same route from Ruby to Nome.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] A reenactment of the serum run was held in 1975, which took six days longer than the 1925 serum run, or more than twice the total time.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Many of the participants were descendants of the original 20.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In 1985, President Ronald Reagan sent a letter of recognition to Charlie Evans, Edgar Nollner, and Bill McCarty, the only remaining survivors.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Nollner was the last to die, on January 18, 1999, of a heart attack.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The relay has been depicted in various media.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Shortly before World War II, Czech teacher and writer František Omelka was fascinated by the story, writing the novella *Štafeta* ("Relay") published in Czech in 1946.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] As an avid Esperantist, Omelka himself translated it into Esperanto, with subsequent translations into German, Dutch, Frisian, Icelandic, Chinese, Japanese, and English.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The serum run was featured in the 1949 animated short "Daffy Duck Hunt", where Daffy Duck describes his time in a freezer as though he were delivering serum on a dog sled.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In 1976, the story was retold in *Race Against Death: A True Story of the Far North,* by children's author Seymour Reit.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Reit's book was featured in a 1978 episode of *The Book Bird*, a PBS program where host John Robbins illustrated key scenes from the book being discussed.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The 1995 2D hand-drawn animated film *Balto* with music composed by James Roy Horner was loosely based on the events of the final leg of the serum run, although all of the characters besides Balto are fictional for family and children entertainments.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In 2013, a documentary titled *Icebound – The Greatest Dog Story Ever Told*, focused on the aftermath of the events.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] *The Great Alaskan Race*, a 2019 film, produced by Rebel Road Entertainment, is based on the serum run.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] *Togo*, produced by Walt Disney Pictures, debuted on December 20, 2019, on Disney+.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] There is much controversy surrounding Balto's role in the serum run and the statue in Central Park.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He then handed the serum off to Charlie Olson.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Olson carried it 25 miles (40 km) to Bluff where he turned it over to Gunnar Kaasen.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Kaasen was supposed to hand off the serum to Rohn at Port Safety, but Rohn had gone to sleep and Kaasen decided to keep going to Nome.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In all, Kaasen and Balto ran a total of 53 miles (85 km).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] According to Togo's musher, Leonhard Seppala, who was also Balto's owner, Balto was a scrub freight dog that he left behind when he set out on the trip.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He also asserted that Kaasen's lead dog was actually a dog named Fox, but that news agents of the time thought that Balto was a more newsworthy name.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] No record exists of Seppala ever having used Balto as a leader in runs or races prior to 1925, and Seppala himself stated Balto "was never in a winning team".
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Because the pictures and video of Kaasen and Balto taken in Nome were recreated hours after their arrival once the sun had risen, speculation still exists as to whether Balto's position as lead dog was genuine, or was staged or exaggerated for media purposes.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The Central Park statue of Balto was modeled after Balto, but shows him wearing Togo's colors (awards).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Katy Steinmetz, writing in *Time* magazine, also thought that Togo was the greatest sled dog of all time.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Mushers (in order) and the distances they covered.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Most legs were planned to be about 25 miles (40 km) long, generally accepted as an "extreme day's mush".
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The **1939–1940 Winter Offensive** (Chinese: 冬季攻勢) was a major engagement between the National Revolutionary Army and Imperial Japanese Army during the Second Sino-Japanese War.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] It constitutes the first major counter-offensive on multiple fronts of Chinese forces in the war.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Although it failed to achieve its original objectives, later studies have shown that it came as a blow to the Japanese forces.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Japanese military command had not expected the Chinese to be able to launch an offensive operation at such a large scale.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] By April 1940, the Japanese army had successfully fought the operation to a halt.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] However, a Japanese counter-offensive to seize Ningxia failed and was defeated in Suiyuan by Chinese Muslim forces.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Chinese had repulsed two Japanese offensives in the summer at the Battle of Suixian-Zaoyang and in fall at the 1st Battle of Changsha.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] They believed that the Japanese forces were now too dissipated to take and hold new territory and would not be able to launch large offensives unless they received more reinforcements.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] However, by defending interior lines and with control of the lines of communication, they could still shift forces and launch local offensives to damage Chinese forces or mop up guerrillas in the rear areas.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Additionally, during 1939, the Japanese were replacing many of their large four-regiment square Divisions with the smaller three regiment triangular Divisions and weak Independent Mixed Brigades.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] This weakening of forces encouraged the Chinese to plan a large offensive to exploit that fact.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Chinese objective in the offensive was to take the initiative by conducting multiple-front attacks to tie down Japanese forces.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] They intended to use their position of exterior lines to advantage to prevent the Japanese from launching new local offensives or shifting their forces to concentrate for a large offensive.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The main effort was to be by the 2nd, 3rd, 5th and 9th War Areas, located on the more northeastern side of China, closest to Japan, which received all newly trained and reorganized units.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Secondary efforts in support of the main efforts or as diversions were to be conducted by 1st, 4th, 8th, Shandong-Jiangsu and Hebei-Chahar War Areas, further south or west from Japan, with their existing units.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Despite this, the 40th Corps and 27th Corps accomplished their aim of pinning down the Japanese in the Zhangzi and Changzhi area.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] However, in southwestern Shanxi, the main effort of 2nd War Area and of the whole North China offensive failed to seize the major towns on the railroad or Japanese strongpoints that were their objectives or to cut the Tongpu railway, except for the area between Wenxi and Anyi.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] At the end of the campaign, the 2nd War Area claimed that 13,770 Japanese killed or wounded.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The 1st War Area reported that 5,130 Japanese killed, and seems to have accomplished its mission of tying down Japanese troops in its area of operations.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The 8th War Area, after a see-saw campaign, had succeeded in rolling the Japanese back to Baotou in the Battle of Wuyuan.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Guerrilla forces in the Hebei-Chahar and Shandong-Jiangsu War Area carried out attacks but apparently without decisive results, and in the Shandong peninsula they received a serious counterattack.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] In 1937, the Chinese government picked up intelligence that the Japanese planned to install a puppet Hui Muslim regime around Suiyuan and Ningxia, and had sent agents to the region.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The *Middlesboro Daily News* ran an article by Owen Lattimore which reported on Japan's planned offensive into the Muslim region in 1938, which predicted that the Japanese would suffer a crushing defeat at the hands of the Muslims.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Japanese planned to invade Ningxia from Suiyuan in 1939 and create a Hui Muslim puppet state.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The next year, however, the Japanese were defeated by the Kuomintang Muslim Gen.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Ma Hongbin, causing the plan to collapse.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] His Hui Muslim troops launched further attacks against Japan in the Battle of West Suiyuan.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] In Suiyuan, 300 Mongol collaborators serving the Japanese were fought off by a single Muslim who held the rank of major at the Battle of Wulan Obo in April.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Muslim Generals Ma Hongkui and Ma Hongbin defended west Suiyuan, especially in Wuyuan, in 1940.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Ma Hongbin commanded the 81st Corps, which suffered heavy casualties, but they eventually repulsed the Japanese and defeated them.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Japan made heavy use of chemical weapons against China to make up for lack of numbers in combat and because China did not have any poison gas stockpiles of its own to retaliate.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Japan also used poison gas against Chinese Muslim armies at the Battle of Wuyuan and the Battle of West Suiyuan.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] River North Army accomplished little and was driven back behind the river by December 23, freeing up units of the Japanese 13th Division for use elsewhere.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Japanese held Right Flank Army in the Zhongxiang area far from the planned stop line from Xinshi to Songhe and Pingba.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Japanese contained Left Flank Army or (River East Army) far from its final objectives.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Southern Honan Army did attack the enemy 3rd Division in the area north of Yingshan and Xishuanghe and send a strong force to cut enemy lines of communications in the area of Guangshui and Xinyang.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Its main force was to attack in the area of Xinyang and occupy it.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Neither of these objectives was achieved despite the commitment of the 31st Army Group.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Eastern Hupei Guerrilla force did not advance to the enemy rear areas at Guangshui, Huayuan and Hankow to check enemy movement along the railroad.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] They never got near those objectives, leaving the Japanese free to move troops along the rails to meet other attacks.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] One of the main objectives that the Chinese managed to retake was the city of Kaifeng.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] After two weeks of fighting, they managed to liberate the city on December 16th, capturing a good amount of Japanese equipment.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Soon after, however, they were pushed out of the city again.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] According to the history of the 65th Infantry Regiment of the Japanese 13th Division, the number of combat deaths for the regiment in the Winter Offensive was as high as 303.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] After routing the Japanese force coming from Longxian on January 1, the 54th Corps recaptured that town on the 2nd.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Guandu fell on the 4th and Qingtang on January 5.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Japanese retreated to Shatian while 54th Corps advanced southwest to Shijiao.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] On January 3 the 2nd Provisional Corps laid siege to Yingde and took it on the 5th.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] It then continued to advance to Lianjiangkou while Japanese remnants fled southwest and took Qingcheng on the north bank of the Lian River, linking up with Japanese forces across the river to the south.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Subsequently, portions of 64th Corps and 2nd Provisional Corps recovered Qingcheng on January 10.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Across the river the next day 14th Division of 54th Corps recovered Pajiangkou and to the east Conghua fell to the detachment of 35th Army Group.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Yuantan along the Guangzhou–Hankou railway fell the following day.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The main force of 35th Army Group moved along the west bank of the Bei River near Zhaoqing, and 54th Corps and a portion of 12th Army Group moved to take up positions at Hengshi, Liangkou, Lutian and Meikang.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The 4th War Area reported more than 10,300 enemy killed, 100 rifles and large amount of supplies captured.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Chinese Army suffered 6,564 killed, 4,595 wounded, and 2,828 missing in the First Battle of Northern Guangdong from December 17, 1939, to January 10, 1940, and claimed to have captured 1 Japanese officer and 1 Japanese soldier.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Japanese 21st Army suffered 293 killed and 1,281 wounded in the Wengyuan-Yingde operation from the middle to the end of December 1939 and claimed to have killed 16,312 and captured 1,196 Chinese troops.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] According to each participating Japanese units' battle report, the 18th Division (excluding the 56th Infantry Regiment) suffered 62 killed, 162 wounded, and 1 missing in the Wengyuan-Yingde operation from December 14, 1939, to January 10, 1940.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The 56th Infantry Regiment of the 18th Division suffered 3 killed and 1 wounded in the operation from December 23 to December 31, 1939.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The 104th Division suffered 302 killed and 735 wounded in the operation from November 20, 1939, to January 13, 1940.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Guards Mixed Brigade suffered 106 killed, 221 wounded, and 20 missing in the operation from December 16, 1939, to January 4, 1940.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1939-1940-winter-offensive] However, with the restricted frontage, and reinforcements sent from Central China the Japanese were able to shift forces to relieve their forces in South Guangxi.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The **1944 Bulgarian coup d'état**, also known as the **9 September coup d'état** (Bulgarian: Деветосептемврийски преврат, romanized: *Devetoseptemvriyski prevrat*), was a coup that overthrew the government of Kingdom of Bulgaria on the eve of 9 September 1944.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] During the Communist era, official propaganda called the coup the **People's Uprising of 9 September** on the grounds of the broad unrest and the **Socialist Revolution** as it was a turning point politically and the beginning of radical reforms towards Soviet-style socialism.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The USSR had declared war on the Kingdom of Bulgaria 4 days earlier and units of its Third Russian Front of the Red Army had entered Bulgaria 3 days after.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Demonstrations, strikes, revolts broke out in many cities and villages (6 - 7 September) and local government power had been taken by Bulgarian Fatherland Front (FF) forces (without Red Army help) in Varna, Burgas, and other locations.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] As a direct result, the government of Prime Minister Konstantin Muraviev was overthrown and replaced with a government of the FF led by Kimon Georgiev.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Bulgaria immediately joined the Allies and fought against Nazi Germany.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The Kingdom of Bulgaria became a republic after the Bulgarian republic referendum in 1946.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Large-scale political, economic and social changes were introduced to the country.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The coup resulted in Bulgaria entering into the Soviet sphere of influence and the beginning of the Bulgarian People's Republic.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] On 26 August 1944, the government of Ivan Bagryanov had verbally declared Bulgaria's neutrality in the war under the threat of the Red Army's offensive in neighbouring Romania.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] At the same time, in Egypt the government had entered separate peace talks with the United Kingdom and the United States, hoping to secure the dispatch of British and American troops in Bulgaria.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] On the same day, the Central Committee of the Bulgarian Workers' Party (BWP) proclaimed the assumption of power by means of a popular uprising to be its official task.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] A government of the Bulgarian Agrarian National Union (BANU) "Vrabcha 1", until then in opposition, was formed on 2 September 1944, headed by Konstantin Muraviev.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] It continued the peace talks, declared its support for democratic reforms and ordered the withdrawal of German Army troops from Bulgaria.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] At the same time, the guerrilla actions of the partisans did not cease, the alliance with Nazi Germany was not disbanded and no attempts were made to normalize the relations with Moscow, causing the Soviet Union to treat the new government with suspicion.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] On 5 September 1944, the Soviet Union declared war on Bulgaria.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The Central Committee of the BWP and the general staff of the People's Liberation Revolt Army commenced, on 5 September, planning of a coup d'état.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The plan was further detailed on 8 September.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] According to the plan, the coordinated actions of the partisans, the BWP combat groups and the pro-Fatherland Front army detachments would assume power and effective control of government during the night of 9 September.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The stated goal of the coup d'état was the "overthrowing of the fascist authorities and the establishment of popular-democratic power of the Fatherland Front".
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Unrest began all around Bulgaria on 6 September and 7 September, with the strikes of the Pernik miners and the Sofia tram employees, as well as the general strikes in Plovdiv and Gabrovo.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The prisons in Pleven, Varna and Sliven had their political prisoners released; 170 localities were entered by partisan detachments between 6 September and 8 September.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] In many cities and villages, the strikes and meetings grew into armed clashes with the police, with victims on both sides.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] On 8 September, the Red Army entered Bulgaria meeting with no opposition on the order of the new Bulgarian government.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] On the eve of 9 September, army units together with Fatherland Front detachments captured key locations in Sofia, such as the Ministry of War, the Ministry of Internal Affairs, the post, the telegraph, the radio, and the railway station.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] On 9 September, on the order of the NOVA commander-in-chief Dobri Terpeshev, all partisan units descended from the mountains and took over villages and cities' governments.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] In most places, this was not met with much resistance, but in other cases army and police units loyal to the old government put up violent resistance to the Fatherland Front forces.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] In Sofia, Plovdiv, the region of Pernik, Shumen and Haskovo the old regime's supporters were defeated by military action with the army coming under the effective control of the Fatherland Front.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The establishment of the new leadership happened at the latest in Haskovo, where partisans and other antifascists seized the artillery barracks on 12 September, but suffered many casualties, as the negotiations with the commanding officers failed to reach a compromise.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] As of 9 September, the Red Army had not reached Sofia but remained in northeastern Bulgaria, as the Bulgarian communists were capable of assuming power without any aid.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The Fatherland Front government included representatives of the BWP, BANU "Pladne", the Bulgarian Social Democratic Workers' Party (Broad Socialists) and Zveno.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The former Prime Minister Konstantin Muraviev was arrested, as were Tsar Simeon II's regents, members of the former government, and some army detachment heads.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] On 10 September, the police was abolished and replaced with a popular militia consisting mainly of recent partisans; 8,130 political prisoners were released from the prisons, and the concentration camps of the former regime (e.g.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Gonda voda, Krasto pole, Lebane) were closed down.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The fascist organizations were banned, as were their publications.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The former regents, Prince Kiril, Bogdan Filov, and Nikola Mihov, were executed on 1 February 1945.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] On 8 September 1946, a referendum about the further destiny of the monarchy was held.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Based on the results of the referendum, Bulgaria was declared People's Republic on 15 September 1946.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] After 9 September 1944, the Bulgarian Army joined the Third Ukrainian Front and contributed to the defeat of Nazism in Europe, helping drive out the Germans from much of Yugoslavia and Hungary, reaching as far as Klagenfurt in Austria by April 1945.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Although Bulgaria was not recognized as a true member of the Allies, it still managed to retain Southern Dobruja which it had acquired in 1940 per the Treaty of Craiova.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] In December 1944, the People's Court was formed by the government of Kimon Georgiev.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Its stated goal was to condemn the persons guilty for Bulgaria's participation in World War II.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Between 4,000 and 30,000 people were killed or missing in just the first four months after the communist regime overtook Bulgaria.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Later, the Bulgarian Communist Party consolidated its leading role in the ruling Fatherland Front coalition, reducing its members from 5 to 2 political parties (the other being the Agrarian Union), leading to the BCP's sole domination over Bulgarian politics up until 1989.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The Tarnovo Constitution was overthrown and replaced in 1947 by the new pro-communist republican Dimitrov Constitution after the successful republic referendum in 1946.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The **1944 Romanian coup d'état**, better known in Romanian historiography as the **Act of 23 August** (Romanian: *Actul de la 23 august*), was a coup d'état led by King Michael I of Romania during World War II on 23 August 1944.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] With the support of several political parties, the king removed the government of Ion Antonescu, which had aligned Romania with Nazi Germany, after the Axis front in northeastern Romania collapsed in the face of a successful Soviet offensive.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The Romanian Army declared a unilateral ceasefire with the Soviet Red Army on the Moldavian front, an event viewed as decisive in the Allied advances against the Axis powers in the European theatre of World War II.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The coup was supported by the Romanian Communist Party, the Social Democratic Party, the National Liberal Party, and the National Peasants' Party who had coalesced into the National Democratic Bloc in June 1944.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] According to Silviu Brucan, the two main conspirators from the Communist Party's side were Emil Bodnăraș and Lucrețiu Pătrășcanu, who contacted King Michael to prepare a *coup d'état* against Ion Antonescu.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The first meeting between King Michael's representatives with the Communists was during the night of 13–14 June 1944 in a secret house of the communists, at 103 Calea Moșilor.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Apart from the two communist conspirators, participants in the meeting were Gen.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Dumitru Dămăceanu, while King Michael was represented by Baron Ioan Mocsony-Stârcea (marshal of the palace), Mircea Ionnițiu (private secretary) and Grigore Niculescu-Buzești (diplomatic adviser).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The King's representatives presented the Gigurtu plan, through which the King would meet Baron Manfred Freiherr von Killinger, the German ambassador in Bucharest, to discuss the replacement of Antonescu with a cabinet led by Ion Gigurtu.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The Communist Party thought that this plan was "naïve and dangerous", as it would have alerted the Gestapo and that it would have meant even more German espionage.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] After this, a coalition government of the National Democratic Bloc (the National Peasants' Party, the National Liberal Party, the Social Democratic Party and the Romanian Communist Party) would take power.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] This proposal was accepted by both the military representatives and the King's advisers, who then convinced King Michael that it was the best solution.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] On 23 August 1944, the king joined with pro-Allied opposition politicians and led a successful coup with support from the army.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The king, who was initially considered to be not much more than a "figurehead", was able to successfully depose Antonescu.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The king offered a non-confrontational retreat to Killinger, but the Germans considered the coup "reversible" and tried to turn the situation around by military attacks.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] On 23 August 1944, the King met with Prime Minister Ion Antonescu, Foreign Affairs Minister Mihai Antonescu (no relation) and General Constantin Sănătescu.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] During discussions that lasted an hour, Ion Antonescu informed the King of the situation at the frontlines.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] King Michael asked Antonescu to get out of the war and sign an armistice with the Allies and the Soviets.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Antonescu retorted that the armistice would be nullified by Germany and refused to commit to an armistice, especially with the Soviet Union.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] A colonel and four soldiers came in and arrested the Prime Minister.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Later that night, at 10 pm, the King announced over the radio that Antonescu had been deposed and an armistice with the Allied Powers and the Soviet Union would be accepted.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The Romanian forces — namely the First Army, the Second Army (under formation), the remnants of the Third Army and the Fourth Army (one corps) — were under orders from the king to defend Romania against any German attacks.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The king then offered to put Romania's battered armies on the side of the Allies.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Hungarian-American historian John Lukacs praised the coup, writing: "In August 1944, the Rumanians executed the most successful *coup d'etat* during World War II.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Due to Romania's successful defection, most of the country's economy had survived virtually intact.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The ensuing reconstruction of the oil industry showed that Romania had less power of refusal under Stalin than under Hitler.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Unlike Italy's earlier capitulation, Romania's initiative began to unravel the Axis.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Within one month, Bulgaria and Finland also changed sides, the Slovak National Uprising began, and a failed coup was attempted in Croatia on 18 September.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Economically, Albert Speer regarded Romania's defection as decisive, because it not only deprived the Axis of Romanian oil but also definitively cut off access to vital supplies of Turkish chromium.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The loss of Romania's oil resulted in Hitler's first admission that the war was lost.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] All of these were accomplished with minimal damage to Romanian infrastructure, as the country's core never became a battlefield.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The coup also marked the last instance when Romania's actions significantly influenced the wider course of the war.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The coup sped the Red Army's advance into Romania.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Formal Allied recognition of the *de facto* change of orientation of Romania in the war came on 12 September 1944.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Until this date, Soviet troops started moving into Romania, taking approximately 140,000 Romanian prisoners of war.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] About 130,000 Romanian POWs were transported to the Soviet Union, where many perished in prison camps.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The armistice was signed on the same date, 12 September 1944, on Allied terms.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] In line with Article 14 of the Armistice Agreement, two Romanian People's Tribunals were set up to try suspected war criminals.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Article 19 stipulated the return to Romania of "Transylvania or the greater part of it".
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] This phrasing conveyed the possibility of a revision of the Treaty of Trianon border, and it was meant to tempt Hungary to also cease fighting alongside Germany.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] At the same time the article also declared Vienna Award "null and void".
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] On 15 October 1944, regent of Hungary Miklós Horthy indeed tried to follow Romania's example and negotiate a surrender, but his attempt was thwarted.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Northern Transylvania was under Soviet military administration from November 1944 to March 1945.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] On 9 March 1945, three days after the formation of the Petru Groza cabinet, Stalin approved the return of all of Northern Transylvania to Romanian administration.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Subsequent Hungarian efforts to recover part of Northern Transylvania were in vain.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] In October 1944, Winston Churchill, Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, as part of a proposed agreement with Soviet leader Joseph Stalin on how to divide Eastern Europe into spheres of influence after the war.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] It was reportedly agreed that Soviet Union would have a "90% share of influence" in Romania.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The Romanian Army, from the armistice until the end of the war, were fighting alongside the Soviets against Germany and its remaining allies.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] They fought in Transylvania, Hungary and Czechoslovakia.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] In May 1945 the Romanian First and Fourth Armies took part in the Prague Offensive.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The Romanians suffered a total of 169,822 casualties (in all causes) fighting on the Allied side.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Ion Antonescu was placed under arrest; the new prime minister, Lt.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Constantin Sănătescu, gave custody of Antonescu to Romanian communists who would turn the former dictator over to the Soviets on 1 September.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] He was later returned to Romania, where he was tried and executed in 1946.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] For his actions, King Michael was awarded the Soviet Order of Victory by Joseph Stalin in 1945.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] He was also awarded the highest degree (Chief Commander) of the Legion of Merit by President Harry S.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Nevertheless, he functioned as little more than a figurehead under the new régime.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] He was finally forced to abdicate and leave the country in 1947.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] This allowed the Communists to set up a communist government.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Michael remained in exile until after the 1989 Romanian revolution and was only allowed to return to the country in 1992.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The **1964 Alaska earthquake**, also known as the **Great Alaska earthquake** and **Good Friday earthquake**, occurred at 5:36 PM AKST on Good Friday, March 27, 1964.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Across south-central Alaska, ground fissures, collapsing structures, and tsunamis resulting from the earthquake caused about 139 deaths.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Lasting four minutes and thirty-eight seconds, the magnitude 9.2–9.3 megathrust earthquake remains the most powerful earthquake ever recorded in North America and the second most powerful earthquake ever recorded in the world since modern seismography began in 1900.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Six hundred miles (970 km) of fault ruptured at once and moved up to 60 ft (18 m), releasing about 500 years of stress buildup.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Soil liquefaction, fissures, landslides, and other ground failures caused major structural damage in several communities and much damage to property.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Anchorage sustained great destruction or damage to many inadequately earthquake-engineered houses, buildings, and infrastructure (paved streets, sidewalks, water and sewer mains, electrical systems, and other man-made equipment), particularly in the several landslide zones along Knik Arm.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Two hundred miles (320 km) southwest, some areas near Kodiak were permanently raised by 30 feet (9 m).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Southeast of Anchorage, areas around the head of Turnagain Arm near Girdwood and Portage dropped as much as 8 feet (2.4 m), requiring reconstruction and fill to raise the Seward Highway above the new high tide mark.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] In Prince William Sound, Port Valdez suffered a massive underwater landslide, resulting in the deaths of 32 people between the collapse of the Valdez city harbor and docks and inside the ship that was docked there at the time.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Nearby, a 27-foot (8.2 m) tsunami destroyed the village of Chenega, killing 23 of the 68 people who lived there.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The survivors outran the wave, climbing to high ground.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Post-quake tsunamis severely affected Whittier, Seward, Kodiak, and other Alaskan communities, as well as people and property in British Columbia, Washington, Oregon, and California.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Tsunamis also caused damage in Hawaii and Japan.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Evidence of motion directly related to the earthquake was also reported from Florida and Texas.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] UTC), a fault between the Pacific and North American plates ruptured near College Fjord in Prince William Sound.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The epicenter of the earthquake was 12.4 mi (20.0 km) north of Prince William Sound, 78 miles (126 km) east of Anchorage and 40 miles (64 km) west of Valdez.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The focus occurred at a depth of approximately 15.5 mi (24.9 km).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Ocean floor shifts created large tsunamis (up to 220 feet (67 m) in height), which resulted in many of the deaths and much of the property damage.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The earthquake also caused large rockslides, resulting in great property damage.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Vertical displacement of up to 38 feet (12 m) occurred, affecting an area of 100,000 square miles (260,000 km2) within Alaska.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Studies of ground motion have led to a peak ground acceleration estimate of 0.14–0.18 *g*.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The earthquake was assigned a maximum Modified Mercalli intensity of X (*Extreme*).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Shaking was felt across much of Alaska and parts of western Yukon and British Columbia in Canada.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The Alaska earthquake was a subduction zone (megathrust) earthquake, caused by an oceanic plate sinking under a continental plate.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The fault responsible was the Aleutian Megathrust, a reverse fault caused by a compressional force.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] This caused much of the uneven ground, the result of shifting to the opposite elevation.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Uplift occurred across 520,000 km2 (200,000 sq mi) from southern Kodiak to Prince William Sound and further east of the sound.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The maximum uplift was in Montague Island, where the ground was raised 13–15 m (43–49 ft) relative to sea level.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The uplift also affected Kodiak, Sitkalidak, and Sitkinak islands.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Subsidence was observed for 285,000 km2 (110,000 sq mi) from north and west of the sound, in Chugach Mountains, most of Kenai Peninsula, and almost all the Kodiak Island group.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Two types of tsunami were produced by this subduction zone earthquake.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] There was a tectonic tsunami produced in addition to about 20 smaller and local tsunamis.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] These smaller tsunamis were produced by submarine and subaerial landslides and were responsible for the majority of the tsunami damage.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Tsunami waves were noted in over 20 countries, including Peru, New Zealand, Papua New Guinea, Japan, Mexico, and in the continent of Antarctica.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The largest tsunami wave was recorded in Shoup Bay, near Valdez, Alaska, with a height of about 220 ft (67 m).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] As a result of the earthquake, 139 people are believed to have died: Fifteen died as a result of the earthquake itself and another 124 died from the subsequent tsunamis in Alaska, Oregon, and California.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Five died from the tsunami in Oregon, and 13 died from the tsunami in California, mostly in or near Crescent City.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Property damage was estimated at $116 million ($894 million in 2024 dollars).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Most damage occurred in Anchorage, 75 mi (121 km) northwest of the epicenter.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Anchorage was not hit by tsunamis, but downtown Anchorage was heavily damaged, and parts of the city built on sandy bluffs overlying "Bootlegger Cove clay" near Cook Inlet, most notably the Turnagain neighborhood, suffered landslide damage.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The neighborhood lost 75 houses in the landslide, and the destroyed area has since been turned into Earthquake Park.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The Government Hill school suffered from the Government Hill landslide, leaving it in two jagged, broken pieces.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Land overlooking the Ship Creek valley near the Alaska Railroad yards also slid, destroying many acres of buildings and city blocks in downtown Anchorage.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Most other areas of the city were only moderately damaged.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The concrete control tower at Anchorage International Airport collapsed, killing the controller on the top floor, as well as trapping two cooks on the first floor, who were later rescued.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] 10th Avenue suffered peripheral damage, but only one block away the recently completed (and still unoccupied) Four Seasons Building on Ninth Avenue collapsed completely, with the concrete elevator shafts sticking up out of the rubble like a seesaw.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The hamlets of Girdwood and Portage, located 30 and 40 mi (48 and 64 km) southeast of central Anchorage on the Turnagain Arm, were destroyed by subsidence and subsequent tidal action.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Girdwood was relocated inland and Portage was abandoned.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] About 20 miles (32 km) of the Seward Highway sank below the high-water mark of Turnagain Arm; the highway and its bridges were raised and rebuilt in 1964–66.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Most coastal towns in the Prince William Sound, Kenai Peninsula, and Kodiak Island areas, especially the major ports of Seward, Whittier and Kodiak were heavily damaged by a combination of seismic activity, subsidence, post-quake tsunamis and/or earthquake-caused fires.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Valdez with 32 dead was not totally destroyed, but after three years, the town relocated to higher ground four miles (6.4 km) west of its original site.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Some Alaska Native villages, including Chenega and Afognak, were destroyed or damaged.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The earthquake caused the ballistic missile detection radar of Clear Air Force Station to go offline for six minutes, the only unscheduled interruption in its operational history.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Near Cordova, the Million Dollar Bridge crossing the Copper River also suffered damage, with Span #4 slipping off its pylon and collapsing.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The community of Girdwood was also confined to the southern side of the Seward Highway when water rushed into Turnagain Arm and flooded or destroyed any buildings left standing to the north of the highway.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Only the ground immediately along the highway and that on the north side of the road dropped, prompting geologists to speculate that Girdwood may rest upon an ancient cliff face covered by thousands of years of sediment and glacial deposits.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] A 4.5 ft (1.4 m) wave reached Prince Rupert, British Columbia, just south of the Alaska Panhandle, about three hours after the earthquake.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The tsunami then reached Tofino, on the exposed west coast of Vancouver Island, and traveled up a fjord to hit Port Alberni twice, washing away 55 homes and damaging 375 others.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The towns of Hot Springs Cove, Zeballos, and Amai also saw damage.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The damage in British Columbia was estimated at CA$10 million ($100 million in 2025 Canadian dollars or $96 million in 2025 US dollars).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Ten people were killed by the tsunami in Crescent City, California, and one other man was killed near Requa, California after being swept out to sea while fishing in the Klamath River.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Four children were killed while camping with their parents on the Oregon coast at Beverly Beach State Park.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] An additional death that is sometimes attributed to the tsunami took place in Bolinas, California; a fisherman wading into a seaside channel at Duxbury Point was swept into the ocean by a strong surge that took place 13 hours after the initial tidal surge.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Crescent City was particularly hard-hit, with 30 blocks destroyed, representing half of the city's waterfront business district.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The total damage to Crescent City was estimated at $7.4 million ($76 million in 2025 dollars).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Other coastal towns and harbors in the Pacific Northwest, California, and Hawaii were damaged, often extensively.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Damage to harbors and boats occurred as far south as Long Beach, California.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Effects of the earthquake were even noted as far east as Freeport, Texas, where tide gauges recorded waves similar to seismic surface waves.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Seiches were detected in wells in countries around the world, including England, Namibia, and Australia.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] There were hundreds of aftershocks in the first weeks following the main shock.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] In the first day alone, eleven major aftershocks with a magnitude greater than 6.0 were recorded.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Nine more struck over the next three weeks.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] In all, thousands of aftershocks occurred in the months following the quake, and smaller aftershocks continued to strike the region for more than a year.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Alaska had never experienced a major disaster in a highly populated area before, and had very limited resources for dealing with the effects of such an event.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] In Anchorage, at the urging of geologist Lidia Selkregg, the City of Anchorage and the Alaska State Housing Authority appointed a team of 40 scientists, including geologists, soil scientists, and engineers, to assess the damage done by the earthquake to the city.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The team, called the Engineering and Geological Evaluation Group, was headed by Dr.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Schmidt, a geology professor at the University of Alaska Anchorage.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The team of scientists came into conflict with local developers and downtown business owners who wanted to immediately rebuild; the scientists wanted to identify future dangers to ensure that rebuilt infrastructure would be safe.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The team produced a report on May 8, 1964, just a little more than a month after the earthquake.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The United States military, which has a large active presence in Alaska, also stepped in to assist within moments of the end of the quake.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Army rapidly re-established communications with the lower 48 states, deployed troops to assist the citizens of Anchorage, and dispatched a convoy to Valdez.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] On the advice of military and civilian leaders, President Lyndon B.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Johnson declared all of Alaska a major disaster area the day after the quake.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Coast Guard deployed ships to isolated coastal communities to assist with immediate needs.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Bad weather and poor visibility hampered air rescue and observation efforts the day after the quake, but on Sunday the 29th the situation improved and rescue helicopters and observation aircraft were deployed.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] A military airlift immediately began shipping relief supplies to Alaska, eventually delivering 2,570,000 pounds (1,170,000 kg) of food and other supplies.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Broadcast journalist Genie Chance assisted in recovery and relief efforts, staying on the KENI air waves over Anchorage for more than 24 continuous hours as the voice of calm from her temporary post within the Anchorage Public Safety Building.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] She was effectively designated as the public safety officer by the city's police chief.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Army Corps of Engineers led the effort to rebuild roads, clear debris, and establish new townsites for communities that had been completely destroyed, at a cost of $110 million.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] The West Coast and Alaska Tsunami Warning Center was formed as a direct response to the disaster.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Federal disaster relief funds paid for reconstruction and financially supported the devastated infrastructure of Alaska's government, spending hundreds of millions of dollars that helped keep Alaska financially solvent until the discovery of significant oil deposits at Prudhoe Bay.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/1964-alaska-earthquake] Defense Department, the Alaska National Guard established the Alaska Division of Emergency Services to respond to any future disasters.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] It was the only military campaign of World War II fought on North American soil.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The islands' strategic value was their ability to control Pacific transportation routes.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Congress in 1935, "I believe that in the future, whoever holds Alaska will hold the world.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] I think it is the most important strategic place in the world." The Japanese reasoned that their control of the Aleutians would prevent a possible joining of forces by the Americans and the Soviets and future attack on the Japanese mainland via the Kuril Islands.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Similarly, the U.S. feared that the islands could be used as bases from which to launch air raids on West Coast cities such as Anchorage, Seattle, San Francisco, or Los Angeles.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Following two aircraft carrier-based attacks on the American naval base at Dutch Harbor, the Imperial Japanese Navy occupied the islands of Attu and Kiska in June 1942.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The remoteness of the islands and the challenges of weather and terrain delayed a larger American-Canadian force sent to eject them for nearly a year.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] A battle to reclaim Attu was launched on 11 May 1943 and completed after a final Japanese banzai charge on 29 May.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] On 15 August 1943 an invasion force landed on Kiska in the wake of a sustained three-week barrage, only to discover that the Japanese had withdrawn from the island on 29 July.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The campaign is known as the "Forgotten Battle" because it has been overshadowed by other events in the war.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Many military historians believe that the Japanese invasion of the Aleutians was a diversionary or feint attack during the Battle of Midway that was meant to draw out the U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Pacific Fleet from Midway Atoll, as it was launched simultaneously under the same commander, Isoroku Yamamoto.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Some historians have argued against that interpretation and believe that the Japanese invaded the Aleutians to protect their northern flank and did not intend it as a diversion.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Before the Empire of Japan entered World War II, the Imperial Japanese Navy had gathered extensive information about the Aleutians but had no up-to-date information regarding military developments on the islands.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Admiral Isoroku Yamamoto provided the Japanese Northern Area Fleet with a force of two non-fleet aircraft carriers, five cruisers, twelve destroyers, six submarines, and four troop transports, along with supporting auxiliary ships.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] With that force, Hosogaya was to launch an air attack against Dutch Harbor then follow with an amphibious attack upon Adak Island, 480 miles (770 km) to the west.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Hosogaya was instructed to destroy whatever American forces and facilities were found on Adak, but the Japanese did not know the island was undefended.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Hosogaya's troops were to return to their ships and become a reserve for two additional landings: the first on Kiska, 240 miles (390 km) west of Adak, the other on the Aleutians' westernmost island, Attu, 180 miles (290 km) west from Kiska.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Army strength, less air force personnel, at those three bases totaled no more than 2,300, composed mainly of infantry, field and anti-aircraft artillery troops, and a large construction engineer contingent, which was used in the construction of bases.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The Army Air Force's Eleventh Air Force consisted of 10 B-17 Flying Fortress heavy bombers and 34 B-18 Bolo medium bombers at Elmendorf Airfield, and 95 P-40 Warhawk fighters divided between Fort Randall and Fort Glenn.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The forward headquarters was set up at Fort Geely, while the rear units were stationed at Fort Richardson.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The naval commander was Rear Admiral Robert A.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Theobald, commanding Task Force 8 afloat, who as Commander North Pacific Force (ComNorPac) reported to Nimitz in Hawaii.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Task Force 8 consisted of five cruisers, thirteen destroyers, three tankers, six submarines, as well as naval aviation elements of Fleet Air Wing Four.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Once the enemy planes were removed, Naval Task Force 8 would engage the enemy fleet and destroy it.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] On the afternoon of 2 June, a naval patrol plane spotted the approaching Japanese fleet, reporting its location as 800 nautical miles (1,500 km; 920 mi) southwest of Dutch Harbor.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Eleventh Air Force was placed on full alert.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Shortly thereafter bad weather set in, and no further sightings of the fleet were made that day.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Before the attack on Dutch Harbor, the Army's 4th Infantry Regiment, under command of Colonel Percy E.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] LeStourgeon, was established at Fort Richardson.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] LeStourgeon had previously designed a layout of base facilities—such as isolation of weapons and munitions depots—to protect against enemy attack.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Making use of weather cover, the Japanese made a two-day aerial bombing of continental North America for the first time in history.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The striking force was composed of Nakajima B5N2 "Kate" torpedo bombers from the carriers *Jun'yō* and *Ryūjō*.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] However, only half of the striking force reached their objective.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The rest either became lost in the fog and darkness and crashed into the sea or returned to their carriers.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Seventeen Japanese planes found the naval base, the first arriving at 05:45.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] As the Japanese pilots looked for targets to engage, they came under intense anti-aircraft fire and soon found themselves confronted by Eleventh Air Force fighters sent from Fort Glenn.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Startled by the American response, the Japanese quickly released their bombs, made a cursory strafing run, and left to return to their carriers.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] As a result, they did little damage to the base.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] On 4 June the Japanese returned to Dutch Harbor.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] This time, the Japanese pilots were better organized and prepared.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] When the attack ended that afternoon, Dutch Harbor oil storage tanks were burning, the hospital was partly demolished, and a beached barracks ship was damaged.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Although American pilots eventually located the Japanese carriers, attempts to sink the ships failed because bad weather set in that caused the U.S. pilots to lose all contact with the Japanese fleet.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] However, the weather caused the Japanese to cancel plans to invade Adak with 1,200 men.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The Japanese invasions and occupations of Kiska on 6 June and Attu on 7 June shocked the American public, as the continental United States was invaded for the first time in 130 years since 1815 (during the War of 1812).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The invading forces initially met little resistance from the local Unangax, also known as Aleuts.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Navy had offered to evacuate Attu in May 1942, the Attuan Unangax chief declined.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Little changed for the Unangax under Japanese occupation until September 1942 when Japan's Aleutian strategy shifted.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] It was at this point that the Unangax were taken to Hokkaido, Japan, and placed in an internment camp.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Through the rest of the summer of 1942, aerial raids by either side could be flown only when the weather permitted.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Japan installed a radar warning system on the islands and continued to resupply them, despite heavy disruptions against its shipping by U.S. bombers and submarines.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The establishment of American air bases in Umnak and Cold Bay would add to the threat faced by the Japanese.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The Unangax (Aleuts), the indigenous people of the Aleutian and Pribilof islands, were evacuated following the attacks on Dutch Harbor.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Although they were U.S citizens, their legal status was often treated as that of "wards" of the federal government, a relationship that allowed the federal government to exercise significant control over their autonomy.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The evacuation process was hasty and chaotic.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Unangax residents were often given less than 24 hours' notice, allowed one suitcase or minimal personal items.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Over 880 Unangax were embarked on military transport ships.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The invasion of Attu and imprisonment of the local Unangax became the justification for the United States' policy of forcible evacuation of the Unangax in the Aleutian Islands.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Unangan civilians were placed in internment camps in the Alaska Panhandle.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] On 12 June USS *Gillis* and *Hulbert*, stationed off Atka, received orders to remove the villagers and burn the village to prevent the buildings being used by the Japanese, should they take the island.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Most of the natives were not at the village, as they had scattered to distant fish camps in case of an attack, meaning that by the time they were evacuated to Nikolski and then Unalaska most had been left with no personal possessions.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Furthermore, the removal cleared Unangax homes for use by U.S. troops, who occupied the vacant houses for the duration of the war.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] On 14 June USCGC *Onondaga* was ordered to evacuate the residents of Saint Paul, and on 16 June USAT *Delarof* evacuated the entire communities of Saint Paul and Saint George.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] On the way to southeast Alaska, *Delarof* stopped briefly at Unalaska to pick up the evacuees from Atka.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The evacuation continued at the end of the month when Dutch Harbor was ordered to evacuate Nikolski, Akutan, Kashega, Biorka and Makushin.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Only the Unangax were evacuated, while the white residents of the islands were made to stay behind to help the troops, resulting in the separation of some mixed families.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Japanese men were separated from their Native wives and moved to the internment camps in the center of the United States.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Children had the choice to either stay with their mothers or leave with their fathers.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Transport vessels such as the USAT *Delarof*, were severely overcrowded and lacked basic infrastructure, including drinkable water, food, and medical care.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] In one documented case, a government doctor refused to enter the ship’s hold to provide medical assistance to those on board.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] During the trip, Haretina Kochutin gave birth under these conditions and without assistance.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Her newborn daughter, Dela, died three days later.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Arrangements were hastily made to accommodate the Unangax in the Alaska Panhandle as they were already en route, and they were eventually interned across a handful of locations.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Conditions were poor and lacked the sufficient infrastructure to house the internees.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] About ten percent of the interned population perished before resettlement after the war.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Japanese forces transported some Attuan captives to Otaru, Hokkaido, where they were held as prisoners of war for the remainder of the war.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Approximately forty percent of the Attuan prisoners died in captivity due to starvation and malnutrition.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The villagers of Saint Paul spent most of World War II at the Thlinket Packing Company cannery at Funter Bay.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The cannery had previously ceased operation in 1931 and had been used as storage before being acquired by P.E.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] By 1942 the buildings had fallen into disrepair with only a caretaker and his wife living on site when the owners struck a deal with the U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Government on the June 16 to lease the property for $60 per month, and on June 24 the entire native population of Saint George and Saint Paul arrived at Funter Bay.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The following day villagers of St George were shifted to the mine site about one mile away.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The villagers were left to their own devices to make the place livable, building beds and repairing the decaying buildings at the site.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Water was often in short supply and contaminated, and the cabins which had not been intended for winter occupation lacked good insulation or heating.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Across the bay from the cannery, the villagers of Saint George were housed in the shoreside camp of the former Admiralty Alaska Gold Mine.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] By June 1942 the mine had been out of production for more than 15 years and only the onsite caretaker (Rado Pekovich) and one other person lived at the site.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Eventually the mine was leased to the government for $1 per year to house the villagers.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The mining camp facilities were not adequate to house the number of villagers due to electrical hazards, poisonous chemicals left from the mining activities and only two outhouses for the entire population.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Like for the cannery, health and sanitation were chronic problems.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] About 50 miles (80 km) south of Funter Bay was the derelict Killisnoo Herring plant.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Operations there began in the 1870s; in 1928 almost all of the housing burnt down, leaving only the industrial plant and a few nearby buildings.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] By the 1930 census the population had plummeted to only three people from around 300 before the fire.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] When the villagers of Atka arrived here around 25 June 1942 the available buildings included three houses, five cabins, a bunkhouse, a warehouse, a machine shop, a shed and a store.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Most of the buildings were unheated, not built for winter occupation, and the villagers had been unable to bring any luggage.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The villagers were left there with some bedding and four days' worth of food and received little federal attention thereafter and were largely left to fend for themselves.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Like at the other camps Killisnoo suffered from poor water sources, poor sanitation, lack of plumbing and inadequate tools.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Of the 83 villagers resettled at Killisnoo, 17 died during the war due to the conditions of the camp.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] After the villagers were sent to the other camps the children were sent to the institute for schooling.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The first villagers arrived on July 13, consisting of 41 people from Akutan, 18 from Biorka, 20 from Kashega, 8 from Makushin, 72 from Nikolski and 1 from Unalaska.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The remainder of the Unalaskans arrived there in the following weeks; however, sources differ on the date and the number of arrivals.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The villagers were moved on and the camp was dismantled by early September.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The 111 villagers from Unalaska were eventually settled at the cannery at the mouth of Burnett Inlet, located on the West side of Etolin Island after a deal was struck with the owners in late August 1942.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The cannery was built in 1912 and had burned down in 1940 with the loss of many of the buildings.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] When the evacuees arrived they found eleven cabins and a bunkhouse still standing but in a dilapidated state, with a row of small cabins hastily constructed among the burned out ruins of the rest of the side.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] This was the most isolated of the evacuation sites and even though it suffered from overcrowding, lack of transportation, limited water, no bath house and one single outhouse for the entire community, it had the lowest mortality rate of the relocation camps.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] In the spring of 1944, 46 villagers from Biorka, Kashega and Makushin were moved to Burnett Inlet from the Ward Lake camp due to the overcrowding of that facility.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Ward Lake is about 10 miles (16 km) northwest of Ketchikan.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Starting in the 1920s after the construction of a section of the Tongass Highway between Ward Lake and Ketchikan allowed a commercial bus service between the two points, and recreational facilities started being built in the area.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] In 1933 the Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC) was established to provide work and training to the unemployed during the Great Depression and to advance nationwide conservation programs.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The CCC built a small camp with a capacity for 65 men at Ward Lake in 1935, and by 1941 it served as a staging area for the CCC and engineering troops bound for Annette Island for the construction of an airfield.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The CCC had ceased to exist in 1942 and the Unangan villagers were moved into the recently emptied camp.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Unlike the other camps the villagers had easy access to nearby Ketchikan by road through the commercial bus service, and while this allowed the villagers to look for employment it caused some friction with the community.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The internment experience differed significantly across Unangax communities.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] While all were subjected to forced removal, those from the Pribilof Island were specifically exploited as a captive labor force.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The U.S. government compelled the men to leave their families at the internment camps and return to the island to harvest seal pelts.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The pay was low, rather than competitive market wages; the government paid only standard military wages.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Although additional financial incentives were promised, almost none of the men received more than basic army pay, and many were not paid at all.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The seal harvest primarily benefited the Fouke Fur Company, who worked alongside the Fish and Wildlife Service to continue pelt operations in Alaska.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] In 1943, Approximately 117,164 seal pelts were harvested, generating over $465,000, a dramatic increase from 127 pelts harvested in 1942.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The Tlingit, on whose land the camps were constructed without consent, responded to the situation of the Unangax with assistance and hospitality.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Members of the Tlingit provided food, water and shelter to the internees.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Tlingit locals shared traditional knowledge with the Unangax, including teaching Unangax women how to harvest local berries.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Residents also provided material resources; at Killisnoo, Tlingit elder Annie Samato provided water from her property and strawberries from her garden.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Following Samato’s example, many other Tlingit women also shared their berry patches.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] In Angoon, the Tlingit community mobilized to feed the Unangax by hunting deer and fishing to supplement the meager government rations.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Additionally, they provided blankets, mattresses, and medicine, subsidizing federal neglect.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] George wrote protest letters refusing to return to the islands unless they received fair wages ($1 per skin) and improved treatment.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The Alaska Native Brotherhood (ANB) and the Alaska Native Sisterhood (ANS) assisted in challenging the Fish and Wildlife Service authority.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The ANB provided food and winter clothing.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Roy Peratrovich played a role in spreading awareness to try and unite the Unangax in their endeavors.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] While their struggles failed to grant any significant settlements with the federal government, their efforts helped secure the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act (ANCSA) in 1971.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] In October 1942, a group of Women at Funter Bay signed a petition modeled after the Declaration of Independence, demanding better living conditions while asserting “We all have rights to speak for ourselves”.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The Unangax were not permitted to return to their homes until 1944 and 1945.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Upon returning to their communities, many Unangax families found their homes looted and vandalized by the U.S. military personnel.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] According to survivor accounts, such as that of Larcy Chercasen, families discovered broken furniture, barricaded homes, and extensive property damage.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Many businesses, tools, and boats were destroyed, harming the economies of many villages after resettlement.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Through the Aleut Restitution Act of 1988 the federal government formally compensated the Unangax.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Many Americans feared that the Japanese would use the islands as bases to strike within range along the rest of the West Coast.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] On 31 August 1942 American forces occupied Adak Island after scouting it two days earlier.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] It was considered a hostile environment to build an airbase due to weather conditions.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] To keep the Japanese on Kiska occupied, missions were flown there by bombers from the Eleventh Air Force.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] They were escorted by fighter aircraft, including P-38s from Umnak over 600 miles (970 km) away.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Runway construction began immediately following the American landing.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] After 10 September, fighters and bombers were moved into the new Adak airbase and used to launch more bombing raids against Japanese positions on Kiska.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] From September to November, American air raids were able to keep the total number of enemy aircraft low, usually under 14 frames, despite persistent attempts to reinforce their number by the Japanese.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Without supporting carriers in the area, the Japanese were unable to dislodge the American forces on Adak.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Even when they had a few air assets to spare, the Japanese generally avoided direct combat.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Other supplies were also beginning to run low.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] After evacuating Attu, the Japanese contemplated occupying and setting up a new base on either the Semichis or Amchitka but were not able to carry out those plans.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] In February 1943, the Americans successfully occupied Amchitka and built an airstrip there.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Their main losses were a result of bad weather.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Ground attack missions were flown from the new island base, starting with P-38s and P-40s before bombers also joined in.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Their targets included radar installations, parked aircraft, anti-aircraft artillery positions, railway, submarine base, and moored vessels.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The bombings further reduced Japan's ability to supply its bases, hampered its construction of landing strips on Attu and Kiska, and facilitated the recapture of those two islands later that year.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] In April 1943 Japanese surface convoys made their final attempt to break through American naval blockade and resupply troops on Attu and Kiska but were forced to abort after being defeated in battle.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Future Japanese resupply missions would be conducted exclusively by submarines and limited by how much materiel they could bring.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Navy submarines and surface ships had also been patrolling the area.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Kiska Harbor was the main base for Japanese ships in the campaign and several were sunk there, some by warships but mostly in air raids.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] On 5 July 1942 the submarine *Growler*, under command of Lieutenant Commander Howard Gilmore, attacked three Japanese destroyers off Kiska.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] She sank one and heavily damaged the others, killing or wounding 200 Japanese sailors.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Ten days later, *Grunion* was attacked by three Japanese submarine chasers in Kiska Harbor, with two of the patrol craft sunk and one other damaged.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] On 12 May 1943 the Japanese submarine *I-31* was sunk in a surface action with the destroyer *Edwards* 5 mi (4.3 nmi; 8.0 km) northeast of Chichagof Harbor.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] At least three Japanese submarines were sunk near Kiska in June 1943, reportedly on the 11th, 13th, and 22nd.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] A cruiser and destroyer force under Rear Admiral Charles "Soc" McMorris was assigned to eliminate the Japanese supply convoys.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] They met the Japanese fleet in March 1943.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] One American cruiser and two destroyers were damaged, and seven U.S. sailors were killed.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Two Japanese cruisers were damaged, with 14 men killed and 26 wounded.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Japan thereafter abandoned all attempts to resupply the Aleutian garrisons by surface vessels, and only submarines would be used.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] On 11 May 1943 American forces commenced **Operation Landcrab** to recapture Attu.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The invasion force included the 17th and 32nd Infantry regiments of the 7th Infantry Division and a platoon of scouts recruited from Alaska, nicknamed Castner's Cutthroats.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The Army Air Force flew more than 500 sorties in a 20-day period to support the invasion.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] A shortage of landing craft, unsuitable beaches, and equipment that failed to operate in the appalling weather made it difficult however for the Americans to exert force against the Japanese.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Soldiers suffered from frostbite because essential cold-weather supplies could not be landed, and soldiers could not be relocated to where they were needed because vehicles could not operate on the tundra.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Rather than engage the Americans where they landed, Colonel Yasuyo Yamasaki had his forces dig into the high ground far from the shore.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] That resulted in fierce combat, with a total of 3,829 U.S. casualties, with 549 killed, 1,148 wounded, and another 1,200 suffering severe injuries from the cold weather.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Also, 614 Americans died from disease and 318 from miscellaneous causes, mainly Japanese booby traps or friendly fire.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] On 29 May 1943 without warning the remainder of Japanese forces attacked near Massacre Bay.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Recorded as one of the largest banzai charges of the Pacific campaign, Yamasaki penetrated so deep into U.S. lines that Japanese soldiers encountered rear-echelon units of the Americans.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] After furious, brutal, often hand-to-hand combat, the Japanese force was virtually exterminated.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Only 28 Japanese soldiers were taken prisoner, none of them were officers.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] American burial teams counted 2,351 Japanese dead, but it was thought that hundreds more had been buried by bombardment during the battle.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] With its loss of Attu to U.S. forces, Japan was deprived of its only remaining airstrip in the Aleutians, a disadvantage that it could not compensate for because Japanese aviation units were entirely ground-based.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] On 15 August 1943 an invasion force of 34,426 Canadian and American troops landed on Kiska.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Castner's Cutthroats were part of the force, but the invasion consisted mainly of units from the 7th Infantry Division (United States).
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The force also included about 5,300 Canadians, mostly from the 13th Canadian Infantry Brigade of the 6th Canadian Infantry Division, and the 1st Special Service Force, a 2,000-strong Canadian-American commando unit trained in winter warfare techniques.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The force included three 600-man regiments: the 1st was to go ashore in the first wave at Kiska Harbor, the 2nd was to be held in reserve to parachute where needed, and the 3rd was to land on the north side of Kiska on the second day of the assault.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] 87th Regiment of the 10th Mountain Division, the only major U.S. force specifically trained for mountain warfare, was also part of the operation.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] 111 and 14 Squadrons saw active service in the Aleutian skies and scored at least one aerial kill on a Japanese aircraft.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Additionally, three Canadian armed merchant cruisers and two corvettes served in the Aleutian campaign but did not encounter enemy forces.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] It is likely that the main Japanese forces left Kiska on the night of 28 July when its radio became silent.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] During the subsequent two weeks, the U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Navy bombed and shelled the abandoned positions.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Navy fought an inconclusive and possibly meaningless Battle of the Pips 80 mi (70 nmi; 130 km) to the west.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The allied invasion forces encountered no opposition on 15 August, but their total casualties would in the end number 313 due to friendly fire, vehicle accidents, Japanese booby traps and explosives, disease and frostbite.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Like Attu, Kiska offered an extremely hostile environment.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Although plans were drawn up for attacking northern Japan, they were not executed.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Over 1,500 sorties were flown against the Kuriles before the end of the war, including the Japanese base of Paramushir, which diverted 500 Japanese planes and 41,000 ground troops.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The battle also marked the first time that Canadian conscripts were sent to a combat zone in World War II.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The government had pledged not to send draftees "overseas", which it defined as being outside North America.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The Aleutians were considered to be North American soil, which enabled the Canadian government to deploy conscripts without breaking its pledge.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] There were cases of desertion before the brigade sailed for the Aleutians.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] In late 1944, the government changed its policy on draftees and sent 16,000 conscripts to Europe to take part in the fighting.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The battle also marked the first combat deployment of the 1st Special Service Force, but it did not see any action.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] In the summer of 1942, the Americans recovered the Akutan Zero, an almost-intact Mitsubishi A6M2 Zero fighter, which enabled the Americans to test-fly the Zero and contributed to improved fighter tactics later in the war.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] During the campaign, two cemeteries were established on Attu to bury those killed in action: Little Falls Cemetery, at the foot of Gilbert Ridge, and Holtz Bay Cemetery, which held the graves of Northern Landing Forces.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] After the war, the tundra began to take back the cemeteries and so in 1946, all American remains were relocated as directed by the soldiers' families or to Fort Richardson near Anchorage, Alaska.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] On 30 May 1946, a Memorial Day address was given by Captain Adair with a three-volley salute and the sounding of *Taps*.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The Decoration of Graves was performed by Chaplains Meaney and Insko.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] In the spring of 1944 the surviving residents of the Pribilofs were allowed to return home, while the remaining villagers were moved back in the spring of 1945 and the camps were dismantled.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The villagers of Saint Paul and Saint George were returned to their islands and were able to largely resume life as before.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] While the residents of Nikolski were able to return to their village and resume life as before the other villagers were not so lucky.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Atka Island had a military base and airstrip built close to the village which made it a target for the Japanese during the war and when the villagers returned the village was destroyed.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The residents of Unalaska returned to a profoundly changed village with a large number of military installations.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The government did not allow the communities of Attu, Kashega, Biorka and Makushin to return to their villages because the cost of restoring their destroyed villages was deemed too great and they were forced to amalgamate into the other Unangan communities.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Of the 831 Unangax relocated to the camps in Southeast Alaska, 85 perished from the poor conditions.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Many of the United States locations involved in the campaign, either directly or indirectly, have been listed on the National Register of Historic Places, and several have been designated National Historic Landmarks.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The battlefield on Attu and the Japanese occupation site on Kiska are both National Historic Landmarks and are included in the Aleutian Islands World War II National Monument.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Surviving elements of the military bases at Adak, Umnak, and Dutch Harbor are National Historic Landmarks.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The shipwrecked SS *Northwestern*, badly damaged during the attack on Dutch Harbor, is listed on the National Register, as is a crash-landed B-24D Liberator on Atka Island.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] The 2006 documentary film *Red White Black & Blue* features two veterans of the Attu Island campaign, Bill Jones and Andy Petrus.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] It is directed by Tom Putnam and debuted at the 2006 Locarno International Film Festival in Locarno, Switzerland, on 4 August 2006.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Dashiell Hammett spent most of World War II as an Army sergeant in the Aleutian Islands, where he edited an Army newspaper.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] He came out of the war suffering from emphysema.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] As a corporal in 1943, he co-authored *The Battle of the Aleutians* with Corporal Robert Garland Colodny under the direction of Infantry Intelligence Officer Major Henry W.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] In 1980 the Commission on Wartime Relocation and Internment of Civilians was appointed by the U.S.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Congress to conduct a study on the internment of Japanese Americans, this was expanded to also look at the treatment of the Unangax.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Public hearings were held starting in 1981 and testimonies were recorded and survivors began sharing their stories.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] Government passed the Aleut Restitution Act of 1988 which acknowledge the failure of the United States to provide adequate care to the Unangax and provided $12,000 for each survivor as well as a $5 million trust fund to help their descendants.
[src:aleutian-islands-campaign/aleutian-islands-campaign] In 1994 the act was expanded to include funding to cover property damage of churches sustained during the war.
